                                <div class="main-content" >
                                    <section data-title="Introduction"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec1-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec1"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">1 </span>Introduction</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec1-content"><p>Hydrogel, a 3D intricate network of crosslinked polymers swollen with water, has emerged as a highly sought-after biomaterial for a myriad of clinical applications [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 1" title="Sneha KR, Sailaja GS. Intrinsically radiopaque biomaterial assortments: a short review on the physical principles, X-ray imageability, and state-of-the-art developments. J Mater Chem B. 2021;9(41):8569–93." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e870">1</a>]. Initially confined to conventional applications such as biomaterials and drug delivery systems, their versatility has expanded to encompass microfluidics, soft electronics, and nanotechnology [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2" title="Mujtaba J, Liu J, Dey KK, Li T, Chakraborty R, Xu K, Makarov D, Barmin RA, Gorin DA, Tolstoy VP. Micro-bio-chemo-mechanical-systems: micromotors, microfluidics, and nanozymes for biomedical applications. Adv Mater. 2021;33(22):2007465." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR2" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e873">2</a>]. Recent years have witnessed significant advancements in hydrogel technology, driven by collaborative interdisciplinary efforts aimed at enhancing their physicochemical properties for clinical utility. Despite their advantageous features such as biocompatibility, biodegradability, simple fabrication, and tunable permeability, conventional hydrogels encounter challenges related to mechanical weakness [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 3" title="Khalid MY, Arif ZU, Ahmed W. 4D printing: technological and manufacturing renaissance. Macromol Mater Eng. 2022;307(8):2200003. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/mame.202200003&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR3" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e876">3</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 4" title="Noroozi R, Arif ZU, Taghvaei H, Khalid MY, Sahbafar H, Hadi A, Sadeghianmaryan A, Chen X. 3D and 4D bioprinting technologies: a game changer for the biomedical sector? Ann Biomed Eng. 2023;51(8):1683–712. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s10439-023-03243-9&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR4" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e879">4</a>]. Typically, they exhibit stiffness around 10 kPa and toughness below 10 J m<sup>−2</sup>, which limits their effectiveness in scenarios requiring sustained load bearing [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 5" title="Beckett LE, Lewis JT, Tonge TK, Korley LTJ. Enhancement of the mechanical properties of hydrogels with continuous fibrous reinforcement. ACS Biomater Sci Eng. 2020;6(10):5453–73." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR5" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e885">5</a>]. Natural tissue in such applications often demand considerable toughness, strength, and stiffness, underscoring the urgent need for improved hydrogel formulations [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 6" title="Ma Z, Bao G, Li J. Multifaceted design and emerging applications of tissue adhesives. Adv Mater. 2021;33(24):2007663." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR6" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e888">6</a>].</p><p>The degradation profiles of many polymer networks often make them incompatible for long-term in vivo applications because of rapid degeneration, especially in electrolyte solutions, which undermines the attainment of desirable therapeutic effects [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 7" title="Mushtaq F, Raza ZA, Batool SR, Zahid M, Onder OC, Rafique A, Nazeer MA. Preparation, properties, and applications of gelatin-based hydrogels (GHs) in the environmental, technological, and biomedical sectors. Int J Biol Macromol. 2022;218:601–33." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR7" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e894">7</a>]. Furthermore, the damage propagation and accumulation within hydrogel networks can lead to a loss of structural integrity, potentially shortening the hydrogel’s functional lifespan [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 8" title="Wang W, Narain R, Zeng H. Rational design of self-healing tough hydrogels: a mini review. Front Chem. 2018;6:497." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR8" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e897">8</a>]. Addressing these challenges has prompted efforts to design materials with enhanced stretchability and toughness properties. However, formulating hydrogels for therapeutic application that are both chemically and morphologically stable and are also mechanically robust remains a significant challenge [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 9" title="Fuchs S, Shariati K, Ma M. Specialty tough hydrogels and their biomedical applications. Adv Healthcare Mater. 2020;9(2):1901396." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e900">9</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 10" title="Zhang K, Feng Q, Fang Z, Gu L, Bian L. Structurally dynamic hydrogels for biomedical applications: pursuing a fine balance between macroscopic stability and microscopic dynamics. Chem Rev. 2021;121(18):11149–93." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR10" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e903">10</a>]. Several obstacles contribute to this difficulty, including the covalent bonds disruption in tough interpenetrating network hydrogels, poor solubility of hydrophobes hindering hydrophobic associations, and limitations on the combined strength of hydrogen bonds due to competition from water molecules for binding sites. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 9" title="Fuchs S, Shariati K, Ma M. Specialty tough hydrogels and their biomedical applications. Adv Healthcare Mater. 2020;9(2):1901396." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e906">9</a>] Additionally, ionic crosslinks are susceptible to mobile ions typically found in physiological conditions. However, natural hydrogels obtained in biological tissues show exceptional mechanical performance because of their complex multicomponent and multihierarchical systems [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 9" title="Fuchs S, Shariati K, Ma M. Specialty tough hydrogels and their biomedical applications. Adv Healthcare Mater. 2020;9(2):1901396." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e910">9</a>]. The extracellular matrices (ECMs) of soft tissues, composed of intertwined elastin and collagen fibers as well as highly hydrated proteoglycan macromolecules, play a pivotal role to determine the outstanding mechanical properties of these tissues [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 11" title="Karamanos NK, Theocharis AD, Piperigkou Z, Manou D, Passi A, Skandalis SS, Vynios DH, Orian-Rousseau V, Ricard-Blum S, Schmelzer CEH. A guide to the composition and functions of the extracellular matrix. FEBS J. 2021;288(24):6850–912." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR11" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e913">11</a>]. For instance, human knee-joint cartilage, including articular cartilage, boasts a high fracture toughness (about 1000 J m<sup>−2</sup>) and can sustain compressive loads of 4–9 MPa for several millions of cycles [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 12" title="Su G, Cao J, Zhang X, Zhang Y, Yin S, Jia L, Guo Q, Zhang X, Zhang J, Zhou T. Human-tissue-inspired anti-fatigue-fracture hydrogel for a sensitive wide-range human–machine interface. J Mater Chem A. 2020;8(4):2074–82." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR12" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e918">12</a>].</p><p>Drawing inspiration from the exceptional mechanical properties of soft tissues, researchers have developed tough hydrogels with impressive strength over the past few decades [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 13" title="Zhao X, Chen X, Yuk H, Lin S, Liu X, Parada G. Soft materials by design: unconventional polymer networks give extreme properties. Chem Rev. 2021;121(8):4309–72." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR13" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e924">13</a>]. In 2003, Gong and colleagues pioneered a dual-network tough hydrogel [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 14" title="Gong JP, Katsuyama Y, Kurokawa T, Osada Y. Double-network hydrogels with extremely high mechanical strength. Adv Mater. 2003;15(14):1155–8." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR14" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e927">14</a>]. This hydrogel featured a densely cross-linked polyelectrolyte first network and a loosely cross-linked polyacrylamide (PAM) second network. Later, a new type of highly stretchy tough hydrogel was made by joining a physical network of dense Ca-alginate with a covalent network of loose PAM. These innovations have led to the establishment of fundamental molecular and structural design strategies. These strategies incorporate energy dissipation into flexible polymer networks, aiding in the creation of robust hydrogels. Moreover, new processing methods such as salting out, freeze casting, and three-dimensional printing are now being used to control the structures of durable hydrogels in microlevel [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 15" title="Zhao Y, Cui J, Qiu X, Yan Y, Zhang Z, Fang K, Yang Y, Zhang X, Huang J. Manufacturing and post-engineering strategies of hydrogel actuators and sensors: from materials to interfaces. Adv Coll Interface Sci. 2022;308: 102749." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR15" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e930">15</a>]. These techniques significantly contribute to the architecture and processing of mechanically robust hydrogels, making them more useful in biomedical applications like medical adhesives and tissue engineering [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 16" title="Correa S, Grosskopf AK, Lopez Hernandez H, Chan D, Yu AC, Stapleton LM, Appel EA. Translational applications of hydrogels. Chem Rev. 2021;121(18):11385–457. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.chemrev.0c01177&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR16" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e933">16</a>]. However, these innovations can sometimes lead to unwanted swelling and a reduction in mechanical properties [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 17" title="Hunt JA, Chen R, van Veen T, Bryan N. Hydrogels for tissue engineering and regenerative medicine. J Mater Chem B. 2014;2(33):5319–38." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR17" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e936">17</a>]. Many existing tough hydrogels have shown a tendency to lose their mechanical integrity during tissue culture or after implantation. Therefore, there is an ongoing need to develop high-water-content, mechanically robust hydrogels that can maintain their properties under challenging in vivo conditions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 18" title="Nachlas ALY, Li S, Davis ME. Developing a clinically relevant tissue engineered heart valve—a review of current approaches. Adv Healthcare Mater. 2017;6(24):1700918." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR18" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e940">18</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 19" title="Yang P, Li Z, Fang B, Liu L. Self-healing hydrogels based on biological macromolecules in wound healing: a review. Int J Biol Macromol. 2023;253:127612." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR19" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e943">19</a>]. This review provides a thorough overview of the latest advancements in mechanically resilient hydrogels for biomedical uses, particularly focusing on artificial soft tissues. It begins by exploring innovative efforts in creating hydrogels with improved mechanical properties, discussing design principles, network structures, and the mechanisms behind their toughness. The review also examines the biocompatibility of these hydrogels and how different crosslinking techniques affect their mechanical strength. Additionally, it looks into the potential of natural-origin tough hydrogels as replacements for biological tissues, highlighting devices with well-defined architectures.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Mechanical properties of hydrogels"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec2-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec2"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">2 </span>Mechanical properties of hydrogels</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec2-content"><p>Polymer gels have long been understood in terms of their resemblance to swollen rubbers, with their mechanical characteristics and structure typically evaluated using the principles of rubber elasticity theory [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Sheiko SS, Dobrynin AV. Architectural code for rubber elasticity: from supersoft to superfirm materials. Macromolecules. 2019;52(20):7531–46." href="#ref-CR20" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e954">20</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Shibayama M. Structure-mechanical property relationship of tough hydrogels. Soft Matter. 2012;8(31):8030–8." href="#ref-CR21" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e954_1">21</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 22" title="Spencer ND, Tysoe WT. Cutting edge of tribology, the: a decade of progress in friction, lubrication and wear. World Scientific, 2015." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR22" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e957">22</a>]. This theory views gels as networks made up of sub-chains connecting adjacent crosslinks. Based on this perspective, the shear modulus of a polymer network, represented by G, can be simply described as [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 23" title="James HM, Guth E. Statistical thermodynamics of rubber elasticity. J Chem Phys. 1953;21(6):1039–49." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR23" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e960">23</a>]:</p><div id="Equ1" class="c-article-equation"><div class="c-article-equation__content"><span class="mathjax-tex">$$G=\upnu {k}_{B}T\left(\text{affine}-\text{network}\right),$$</span></div><div class="c-article-equation__number">
                    (1)
                </div></div><p>where ν signifies the crosslink density, k<sub>B</sub> denotes the Boltzmann constant, and T stands for the absolute temperature. The affine network model, which this discussion references, posits that crosslink junctions remain stationary and move uniformly with the network. Nevertheless, actual networks demonstrate fluctuations in the positions of these crosslinks, thereby lowering the system's free energy. To account for these fluctuations, several models have been proposed, including the phantom network model, the constraint junction model, and the slip-link model [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="James HM, Guth E. Statistical thermodynamics of rubber elasticity. J Chem Phys. 1953;21(6):1039–49." href="#ref-CR23" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1014">23</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Wall FT, Flory PJ. Statistical thermodynamics of rubber elasticity. J Chem Phys. 1951;19(12):1435–9." href="#ref-CR24" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1014_1">24</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 25" title="Flory PJ. Theory of elasticity of polymer networks. The effect of local constraints on junctions. J Chem Phys. 1977;66(12):5720–9." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR25" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1017">25</a>]. For example, the phantom network model suggests that while a small portion of junctions are fixed, the majority fluctuate according to Gaussian statistics. This leads to a modification of equation [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 23" title="James HM, Guth E. Statistical thermodynamics of rubber elasticity. J Chem Phys. 1953;21(6):1039–49." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR23" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1020">23</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 26" title="Cho Z, Wu B, Zhou Y, Zhou F, Liu W, Wang Z. Mussel-inspired hydrogels: from design principles to promising applications. Chem Soc Rev. 2020;49(11):3605–37." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR26" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1023">26</a>]:</p><div id="Equ2" class="c-article-equation"><div class="c-article-equation__content"><span class="mathjax-tex">$$G=\left(\upnu -\mu \right){k}_{B}T\left(\text{phantom}-\text{network}\right),$$</span></div><div class="c-article-equation__number">
                    (2)
                </div></div><p>where μ ≡ 2ν/f. Here, it’s more appropriate to redefine ν and μ to reflect real networks with defects: ν represents the number density of elastically "effective" strands (subchains between crosslinks), and μ denotes the number density of "effective" crosslinks [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 27" title="Treloar LG. The physics of rubber elasticity. 1975." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR27" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1081">27</a>]. The shear modulus is determined from stress-elongation curves or shear experiments, expressed as [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 23" title="James HM, Guth E. Statistical thermodynamics of rubber elasticity. J Chem Phys. 1953;21(6):1039–49." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR23" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1085">23</a>]:</p><div id="Equ3" class="c-article-equation"><div class="c-article-equation__content"><span class="mathjax-tex">$$\sigma =G\left(\uplambda -\frac{1}{{\uplambda }^{2}}\right),$$</span></div><div class="c-article-equation__number">
                    (3)
                </div></div><p>where stress is and is the draw (or compression) ratio. Stress-draw ratio curves for a commercial rubber ring made of natural rubber, vulcanized in bulk (ϕ = 1.0), and in an equilibrium swollen state in toluene at room temperature (ϕ ≈ 0.18), illustrate the differences. The decrease in G due to swelling results from the reduction in ν, where ν = ϕν0, with ν0 and ν representing the number densities of effective chains in the bulk and swollen states, respectively.</p><p>However, analyzing the structure–mechanical property relationship of polymer gels presents greater complexity due to the intricate gel preparation processes and network structures. Copolymerization of monomers and crosslinkers, for example, often leads to nonuniform networks with various topological defects and spatial inhomogeneities. Consequently, the mechanical properties of typical gels are generally poorer than those of swollen rubbers. In the subsequent sections, we delve into the structure–mechanical property relationship of tough gels, beginning with a discussion of the theoretical basis of scattering for polymer solutions and gels, followed by an exploration of the structure–mechanical property relationship.</p><p>The mechanical properties of hydrogels engineered for biomedical applications can be finely tuned to meet specific needs by adjusting crosslinking degrees or controlling temperature during fabrication [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 28" title="Vedadghavami A, Minooei F, Mohammadi MH, Khetani S, Kolahchi AR, Mashayekhan S, Sanati-Nezhad A. Manufacturing of hydrogel biomaterials with controlled mechanical properties for tissue engineering applications. Acta Biomater. 2017;62:42–63." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR28" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1146">28</a>]. Such modifications allow for the precise optimization of hydrogel stiffness, crucial for their performance in various applications. Understanding the multifaceted factors influencing the mechanical behavior of these polymeric materials requires comprehensive analyses that account for the material properties, experimental conditions, and research objectives. For instance, assessing hydrogel elasticity often involves utilizing a Universal Testing Machine, while investigating viscoelastic properties typically requires Dynamic Mechanical Analysis devices or rheometers [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 29" title="Yang Z, Chen X, Xu Z, Ji N, Xiong L, Sun Q. Anti-freezing starch hydrogels with superior mechanical properties and water retention ability for 3D printing. Int J Biol Macromol. 2021;190:382–9." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR29" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1149">29</a>]. It is essential to note that in hydrogels, the Young Modulus is intricately linked to the interaction between water and the gel matrix (Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig1">1</a>). The choice of hydrogel stiffness is important for numerous applications, ranging from selecting suitable materials for seeding osteoblast cells versus adipocytes to crafting heterogeneous prosthetic devices like substitutes for intervertebral discs [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 30" title="Angolkar M, Paramshetti S, Gahtani RM, Al Shahrani M, Hani U, Talath S, Osmani RAM, Spandana A, Gangadharappa HV, Gundawar R. Pioneering a paradigm shift in tissue engineering and regeneration with polysaccharides and proteins-based scaffolds: a comprehensive review. Int J Biol Macromol. 2024; 130643." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR30" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1155">30</a>].</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-1" data-title="Fig. 1"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig1" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 1</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig1_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-1-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig1_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 1" loading="lazy" width="685" height="568"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/1" data-track-dest="link:Figure1 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 1" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-1-desc"><p>Polymers exhibit a variety of stress–strain curves, each portraying distinct properties. Curves (a–c) depict the behavior of glassy polymers, while curve (d) illustrates the rubbery state. At the extremes of these curves lie the crucial points of material breakdown: (a) demonstrating brittleness, whereas (b–d) displaying ductility. In simpler terms, different types of polymers bend and break in different ways under stress. Glassy polymers, as shown in curves (a–c), behave differently from rubbery polymers, represented by curve (d). When pushed to their limits, some polymers snap easily like glass (curve a), while others stretch and deform before breaking (curves b–d). The idea of the figure is taken from ref. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 31" title="Rostiashvili VG, Vilgis TA. Statistical thermodynamics of polymeric networks. In: Kobayashi S, Müllen K, editors. Encyclopedia of polymeric nanomaterials. Berlin Heidelberg: Springer; 2021. p. 1–18." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR31" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1168">31</a>]</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Another valuable technique for evaluating the mechanical properties of different hydrogel types is the compression test. This method involves compressing the hydrogel between two plates to calculate mechanical properties based on applied pressure and compression distance. Unlike extensometer-based tests, the compression test offers versatility in hydrogel geometry, as it is not limited to specific shapes like strips or rings, although it requires a flat surface. However, challenges such as hydrogel bulging, and uneven pressure distribution arise with this approach. Strategies such as confining the hydrogel around its outer edge have been explored to address bulging, although this modification can alter measurement characteristics. Despite these challenges, the compression test has proven useful in studying the mechanical properties of cell-seeded hydrogels in various research endeavors [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 25" title="Flory PJ. Theory of elasticity of polymer networks. The effect of local constraints on junctions. J Chem Phys. 1977;66(12):5720–9." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR25" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1182">25</a>].</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Control of mechanical properties"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec3-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec3"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">3 </span>Control of mechanical properties</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec3-content"><p>In the context of advancing the mechanical characteristics of materials optimization for biomedical purposes, a profound comprehension and adept manipulation of their mechanical properties hold paramount importance [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 32" title="Mohsenian R, Matin Nazar A, Ranjbar F, Saberian M, Yang P, Li W, Jiao P. Triboelectric and piezoelectric materials for smart health in human-integrated healthcare systems. MRS Commun. 2024;14(4):460–79. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1557/s43579-024-00577-w&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR32" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1193">32</a>]. This section intricately examines three distinct methodologies aimed at steering these properties: fine-tuning the co-monomer composition, modulating cross-linking density through augmentation or reduction, and adjusting the polymer formation conditions. Furthermore, we will delve into the interplay between the mechanical traits of hydrogels and their extent of swelling. It is imperative to recognize that alterations within the polymer framework not only affect mechanical attributes but also exert influence over other material behaviors.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec4"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">3.1 </span>Effects of comonomer composition</h3><p>Improving the mechanical toughness of hydrogels in biomedical applications often requires strategic adjustments to the comonomer composition [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 33" title="Wang W, Zhang Y, Liu W. Bioinspired fabrication of high strength hydrogels from non-covalent interactions. Prog Polym Sci. 2017;71:1–25. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.progpolymsci.2017.04.001&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR33" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1203">33</a>]. When hydrogels are made from a blend of comonomers rather than a homopolymer, altering the proportions of comonomers with stronger physical properties can significantly enhance the overall mechanical strength [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 34" title="Erkoc C, Yildirim E, Yurtsever M, Okay O. Roadmap to design mechanically robust copolymer hydrogels naturally cross-linked by hydrogen bonds. Macromolecules. 2022;55(23):10576–89. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.macromol.2c01469&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR34" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1206">34</a>]. Such modifications can impact mechanical toughness by either increasing the stiffness of the backbone polymer or changing the hydrophilicity of the polymer, as demonstrated in previous research.</p><p>An alternative method to modify comonomer composition involves adjusting the quantity and type of cross-linking agent used [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 35" title="Verde-Sesto E, Asenjo-Sanz I, Juranyi F, Pomposo JA, Maiz J. Probing the influence of composition and cross-linking degree on single-chain nanoparticles from poly(tetrahydrofuran-ran-epichlorohydrin) copolymers: insights from neutron scattering, calorimetry, and dielectric spectroscopy. J Colloid Interface Sci. 2025;679:785–97. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jcis.2024.10.027&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR35" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1212">35</a>]. For instance, adding <i>N</i>-vinylpyrrolidone (NVP) to hydroxyethyl methacrylate (HEMA) copolymers led to a significant decrease in Young’s modulus, indicating reduced material strength [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 36" title="Lin J, Chen X, Zhang P, Xue Y, Feng Y, Ni Z, Tao Y, Wang Y, Liu J. Wireless bioelectronics for in vivo pressure monitoring with mechanically-compliant hydrogel biointerfaces. Adv Mater. 2024;36(26):2400181. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/adma.202400181&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR36" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1218">36</a>]. This decrease was particularly noteworthy, with a ten-fold reduction observed as the NVP content increased from 5 to 60%. This outcome is consistent with expectations, as NVP is highly hydrophilic, causing increased swelling compared to HEMA. Moreover, increasing the relative proportion of more hydrophilic monomers can result in greater swelling in the resulting hydrogel. However, this is accompanied by a simultaneous decrease in mechanical strength. These compositional adjustments provide valuable insights into tailoring robust hydrogels for diverse biomedical applications.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec5"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">3.2 </span>Effects of polymerization conditions</h3><p>The final structure of mechanically tough hydrogels for biomedical use is shaped by various reaction conditions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 37" title="Liu B, Li H, Meng F, Xu Z, Hao L, Yao Y, Zhu H, Wang C, Wu J, Bian S, et al. 4D printed hydrogel scaffold with swelling-stiffening properties and programmable deformation for minimally invasive implantation. Nat Commun. 2024;15(1):1587. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-024-45938-0&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR37" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1229">37</a>]. Factors such as reaction time, temperature, and the composition and volume of solvent are critical in determining their properties [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 38" title="Wang Y, Shen L, Yan Y, Gong B, Chen K, Zhu G, Li Z. Ultrasound assisted upper critical solution temperature type switchable deep eutectic solvent based liquid–liquid microextraction for the determination of triazole in water. Anal Chim Acta. 2024;1328: 343172. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aca.2024.343172&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR38" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1232">38</a>]. The choice and amount of solvent can significantly influence the polymerization process. Excessive solvent use may result in the cross-linking agent forming cycles rather than cross-links, which weakens the material [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 39" title="Cheng C, Yang R, Wang Y, Dong X, Fu D, Sheng J, Guo X. High porosity, excellent mechanical strength, interpenetrating network-reinforced double network regenerated cellulose separators for lithium-ion battery. Int J Biol Macromol. 2024;283:137407. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2024.137407&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR39" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1235">39</a>]. Changes in solvent type or characteristics, such as alterations in pH or ionic strength within aqueous solutions, can induce modifications in copolymer structure. The reactivity of monomers is notably affected by ionic strength and pH, potentially leading to shifts in structure or significant compositional changes [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 40" title="Wang B-R, Zhi W-X, Han S-Y, Zhao H-F, Liu Y-X, Xu S-Y, Zhang Y-H, Mu Z-S. Adaptability to the environment of protease by secondary structure changes and application to enzyme-selective hydrolysis. Int J Biol Macromol. 2024;278: 134969. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2024.134969&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR40" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1238">40</a>]. Monomers generally exhibit heightened reactivity in their unionized state or under conditions of high solution ionic strength.</p><p>Research into the copolymerization of HEMA and 2-dimethylaminoethylmethacrylate has unveiled how polymerization conditions influence hydrogel properties [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 41" title="Abbasi E, Ghamkhari A, Ghorbani M, Salati MA, Abbasi F. Facile construction of pH-responsive nanocarrier based on host–guest interactions chemistry for triggered drug delivery. J Polym Res. 2024;31(6):182. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s10965-024-04000-9&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR41" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1244">41</a>]. When a substantial volume of solvent is present, the structure and properties of the polymer differ from those produced in bulk polymerization. Additionally, factors such as reaction time, temperature, and light intensity during photopolymerizations vary. By adjusting these parameters, control over functional group conversion is gained, which profoundly impacts the properties of the resulting hydrogel [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 42" title="El-diehy MA, Farghal II, Amin MA, Ghobashy MM, Nowwar AI, Gayed HM. Radiation synthesis of sodium alginate/gelatin based ultra-absorbent hydrogel for efficient water and nitrogen management in wheat under drought stress. Sci Rep. 2024;14(1):19463. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-024-69333-3&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR42" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1247">42</a>]. Obtaining robust mechanical strength in hydrogels without post-reaction treatments requires enhanced double-bond conversion, which reduces the residual soluble fraction and potentially increases cross-link density. However, post-reaction treatments can also effectively alter the network structure and material strength. Techniques such as introducing compounds that complex with the monomer/polymer or subjecting the polymer to successive freezing and thawing cycles have shown efficacy. Thermally cycling the polymer has been particularly effective in significantly elevating Young's modulus while largely preserving other gel properties.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec6"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">3.3 </span>Effects of cross-linking density</h3><p>The mechanical robustness of hydrogels is predominantly determined by the presence of cross-links within the system [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 43" title="Ghosh A, Kumar S, Singh PP, Nandi S, Mandal M, Pradhan D, Khatua BB, Das RK. Dynamic metal-coordinated adhesive and self-healable antifreezing hydrogels for strain sensing, flexible supercapacitors, and EMI shielding applications. ACS Omega. 2024;9(30):33204–23. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsomega.4c04851&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR43" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1258">43</a>]. Enhanced mechanical strength is closely associated with a higher density of cross-linking. Achieving this elevated cross-linking density is readily accomplished by incorporating a larger quantity of cross-linking agents [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 44" title="Zhang Y-X, Wang Y-S, Chen Y, Luan Q-Y, Ding M-Y, Chen H-H. Effects of secondary cross-linking on the physicochemical properties of sodium alginate-hydrogel and in vitro release of anthocyanins. Int J Biol Macromol. 2024;276: 133926. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2024.133926&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR44" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1261">44</a>]. However, the introduction of an increased number of cross-linking agents can lead to the development of heterogeneities within the polymer networks [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 45" title="Kong VA, Staunton TA, Laaser JE. Effect of cross-link homogeneity on the high-strain behavior of elastic polymer networks. Macromolecules. 2024;57(10):4670–9. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.macromol.3c02565&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR45" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1264">45</a>]. Typically, these highly cross-linked heterogeneities manifest when the concentration of cross-linking agent exceeds 5% during radical polymerization.</p><p>Several studies have delved into the relationship between mechanical properties and cross-linking agent concentration in hydrogels [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 46" title="Cohen Y, Ramon O, Kopelman IJ, Mizrahi S. Characterization of inhomogeneous polyacrylamide hydrogels. J Polym Sci. 1992;30:1055–67. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/polb.1992.090300913&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR46" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1270">46</a>]. For instance, hydrogels based on poly(acrylic acid) (PAA) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 47" title="Hill C, Altgen M, Penttilӓ P, Rautkari L. interaction of water vapour with wood and other hygro-responsive materials. J Mater Sci. 2024;59:7595." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1273">47</a>] copolymers display minor-scale heterogeneities that amplify with higher concentrations of cross-linking agents. While boosting the amount of cross-linking agent enhances material strength, these heterogeneities concurrently diminish the formation of effective cross-links [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 48" title="Moussaid A, Candau SJ, Joosten JGH. Structural and dynamic properties of partially charged poly[acrylic acid) gels: nonergodicity and inhomogeneities. Macromolecules. 1994;27:2102–10. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/ma00086a019&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR48" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1276">48</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 49" title="Greenberg AR, Kusy RP. Viscoelastic behavior of highly crosslinked poly(acrylic acid). J Appl Polym Sci. 1980;25:2795–805. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/app.1980.070251212&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR49" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1279">49</a>]. Within these heterogeneities, the cross-linking agent forms numerous cycles that contribute insignificantly to the mechanical strength of the polymer [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 50" title="Song W, Wen Y, Wang Z, Xu H, Liao Q, Tang Y, Yu D-G, Kim I. Versatile hyper-cross-linked polymers derived from waste polystyrene: synthesis, properties, and intentional recycling. Langmuir. 2024;40(32):16670–89. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.langmuir.4c01041&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR50" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1282">50</a>]. Numerous investigations have underscored the potential for significant enhancement in material strength through increased cross-linking agent concentration [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 49" title="Greenberg AR, Kusy RP. Viscoelastic behavior of highly crosslinked poly(acrylic acid). J Appl Polym Sci. 1980;25:2795–805. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/app.1980.070251212&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR49" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1286">49</a>]. However, adjustments in cross-linking density are anticipated to induce changes in properties beyond strength. Diffusivities, along with release and swelling rates, are expected to decrease, while the maximum degree of swelling is likely to diminish as well. These alterations can impact the desired properties of the material, necessitating a comprehensive re-evaluation as the cross-link density is modified.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Crosslinking mechanism tough hydrogels"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec7-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec7"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">4 </span>Crosslinking mechanism tough hydrogels</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec7-content"><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec8"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">4.1 </span>Physical crosslinking hydrogels</h3><p>Physical crosslinking involves weak interactions between polymeric chains to form a three-dimensional network [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 51" title="Joseph AM, George B. Cross-linking biopolymers for biomedical applications. In: Handbook of biopolymers. Berlin: Springer; 2023. p. 1135–72." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR51" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1302">51</a>]. A weak interaction can occur as a result of hydrogen bonds, coordination bonds, ions, hydrophobic interactions, or van der Waals interactions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 52" title="Parhi R. Cross-linked hydrogel for pharmaceutical applications: a review. Adv Pharm Bull. 2017;7(4):515–30. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.15171/apb.2017.064&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR52" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1305">52</a>]. Polymer chains form junction zones when they contact one another over a certain length as opposed to being connected point to point. It is possible to form hydrogen bonds between polymer two chains within a polymer gel network as well as between polymer chains and water molecules. Hydrogen bonding is so wide-ranging that polymer chains are able to resist stresses applied to the material from stretching or bending [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 53" title="Xie Z, Hu BL, Li RW, Zhang Q. Hydrogen bonding in self-healing elastomers. ACS Omega. 2021;6(14):9319–33. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsomega.1c00462&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR53" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1308">53</a>]. In the hydrogel networks, hydrogen bonds can improve cohesion by acting as cross-linking domains [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 54" title="Yu H, Xiao Q, Qi G, Chen F, Tu B, Zhang S, Li Y, Chen Y, Yu H, Duan P. A Hydrogen bonds-crosslinked hydrogels with self-healing and adhesive properties for hemostatic. Front Bioeng Biotechnol. 2022;10: 855013. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3389/fbioe.2022.855013&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR54" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1311">54</a>]. At the interface between the hydrogel and the substrate, functional groups could form hydrogen bonds and enhance the interfacial interactions. Poly methacrylic acid (PMA) and polyacrylic acid [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 47" title="Hill C, Altgen M, Penttilӓ P, Rautkari L. interaction of water vapour with wood and other hygro-responsive materials. J Mater Sci. 2024;59:7595." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1314">47</a>] make a compound with PEG. These compounds contain hydrogen bonding between the O atom of the PEG and the –COOH group of PAA/PMA [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 55" title="Eagland D, et al. Complexation between polyoxyethylene and polymethacrylic acid-the importance of the molar mass of polyethylene. Eur Polym J. 1994;30:767–73." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR55" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1318">55</a>]. Not only PMA and PEG form hydrogen bonding but also PMA-g-PEG [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 56" title="Bell CL, Peppas NA. Modulation of drug permeation through interpolymer complexed hydrogels for drug delivery applications. J Control Release. 1996;39:201–7. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/0168-3659(95)00154-9&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR56" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1321">56</a>]. In Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig2">2</a>, conventional mechanism of physical crosslinking system have illustrated.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-2" data-title="Fig. 2"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig2" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 2</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig2_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-2-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig2_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 2" loading="lazy" width="685" height="322"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/2" data-track-dest="link:Figure2 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 2" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-2-desc"><p>Schematic representation of physical crosslinking</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The formation of hydrogen bonds is contingent upon the protonation of the –COOH groups, resulting in pH dependent gel swelling [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 57" title="Akhtar MF, Hanif M, Ranjha NM. Methods of synthesis of hydrogels … A review. Saudi Pharm J. 2016;24(5):554–9. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jsps.2015.03.022&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR57" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1347">57</a>]. A particular type of alternative covalent link created by sharing an electron pair from a single atom is designated as a coordination bond. Coordination bonds are created by ligands connecting metal cation centers in an inorganic or organometallic polymer structure. While feeble coordination bonds reversibly break and regenerate, squandering energy, strong coordination bonds and their connections function as permanent cross-links that add flexibility. The gels exhibit unique mechanical capabilities, influence memory ability, and even reversible sol–gel transition by adjusting the bond strength through pH. When a water-soluble and charged polymer crosslinks with an oppositely charged ion is called ionic interaction toward hydrogel. Ionic interaction can happen between two opposite-charged polymers as well as a polymer and a tiny component. Ionic materials exhibited the most favorable healing response over the widest range of temperatures [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 58" title="Xu G, Li C, Chen C, Fu J, Hou T, Zi Y. Dynamics of triboelectric nanogenerators: a review. Int J Mech Syst Dyn. 2022;2:311–24. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/msd2.12058&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR58" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1350">58</a>]. A polymer amphiphile is produced through hydrophobic contact, in which hydrophobic blocks are connected to hydrophilic blocks. The hydrophobic blocks agglomerate as the temperature rises. The concentration of the polymer, the length of the hydrophobic s block, and the polymer's chemical structure all influence the temperature at which the phase transition occurs. Physically cross-linked hydrogels are becoming increasingly popular in the modern day. The following are the different procedures to synthesize physically cross-linked hydrogels. Colloidal silica, agarose, gelatin, and agar are a few materials that physically cross-link [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 59" title="Shamlooh M, Hamza A, Hussein IA, Nasser MS, Salehi S. Gelation kinetics of functionalized silica crosslinked polymeric gels used in conformance control applications. Can J Chem Eng. 2021;99(10):2219–28. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/cjce.23947&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR59" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1353">59</a>]. Physically cross-linked hydrogels include PEG, PBT, PAM, and Pullulan [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 60" title="Hennink WE, van Nostrum CF. Novel crosslinking methods to design hydrogels. Adv Drug Deliv Rev. 2002;54(1):13–36. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/s0169-409x(01)00240-x&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR60" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1356">60</a>]. Physically crosslinked hydrogels are fabricated by hydrophobized polysaccharides, hydrogen bonding, crystallization, ionic contact, and protein interaction. A schematic representation of different physical crosslinking mechanisms is given in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig3">3</a>.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-3" data-title="Fig. 3"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig3" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 3</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig3_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-3-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig3_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 3" loading="lazy" width="685" height="543"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/3" data-track-dest="link:Figure3 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 3" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-3-desc"><p>Schematic illustration of different physical crosslinking mechanisms of polymeric gel. <b>a</b> Hydrogen bonding, <b>b</b> Ionic interactions, <b>c</b> Metal-coordination interactions, and <b>d</b> Hydrophobic interactions</p></div></div></figure></div><p>However, at physiological pH and with the mild condition, ionic interaction can be formed at ambient temperature to give a tough and self-healable hydrogel matrix in presence of various metallic ions, this special type of electrostatic bond can be form, however, it is not necessary to confirm the presence of ionic functionalities in the gel solution [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 61" title="Tu Y, Chen N, Li C, Liu H, Zhu R, Chen S, Xiao Q, Liu J, Ramakrishna S, He L. Advances in injectable self-healing biomedical hydrogels. Acta Biomater. 2019;90:1–20." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR61" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1396">61</a>]. In order to form stereo complexes, lactic acid oligomers that have opposite chirality crosslink with one another in a hydrogel [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 62" title="de Jong SJ, De Smedt SC, Demeester J, van Nostrum CF, Kettenes-van den Bosch JJ, Hennink WE. Biodegradable hydrogels based on stereocomplex formation between lactic acid oligomers grafted to dextran. J Control Release. 2001;72:47–56. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/s0168-3659(01)00261-9&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR62" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1399">62</a>]. As a result of hydrophobic interactions, the polymer is swollen and water is absorbed, forming the hydrogel. In the literature, hydrophobic modification is used to prepare both physically crosslinked and hydrophobic hydrogels using polysaccharides such as chitosan, dextran, pullulan, and carboxymethyl curdlan [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 63" title="Bustamante-Torres M, Romero-Fierro D, Arcentales-Vera B, Palomino K, Magana H, Bucio E. Hydrogels classification according to the physical or chemical interactions and as stimuli-sensitive materials. Gels. 2021;7(4):182. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/gels7040182&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR63" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1402">63</a>]. In physiological conditions, the silk-like domains of these Prolactin crystallize to form a gel following the transformation from a fluid solution to a gel [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 64" title="Wrede P, Schneider G. Concepts in protein engineering and design: an introduction. Walter de Gruyter GmbH &amp; Co KG, 2020." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR64" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1405">64</a>]. Polyacrylic acid [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 47" title="Hill C, Altgen M, Penttilӓ P, Rautkari L. interaction of water vapour with wood and other hygro-responsive materials. J Mater Sci. 2024;59:7595." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1408">47</a>] and PMA form complexes with PEG from the hydrogen bonds between the oxygen of the PEG and the –COOH group of PMAA [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 65" title="Liu G, Ding X, Cao Y, Zheng Z, Peng Y. Shape memory of hydrogen-bonded polymer network/poly (ethylene glycol) complexes. Macromolecules. 2004;37(6):2228–32." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR65" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1412">65</a>]. Due to this interaction, liquids are absorbed and the complex swells at low pH, transforming the system into gel. As a result of crystallization, a strong and highly elastic gel is created by the freezing–thawing process [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 66" title="Adelnia H, Ensandoost R, Moonshi SS, Gavgani JN, Vasafi EI, Ta HT. Freeze/thawed polyvinyl alcohol hydrogels: present, past and future. Eur Polymer J. 2022;164: 110974." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR66" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1415">66</a>]. PVA hydrogels can be formed by physically crosslinking through repeated freezing/thawing methods, or chemically crosslinked with glutaraldehyde or epichlorohydrin.</p><p>On the other hand, the dynamic covalent bonds enable the polymer network to adapt in response to external stimuli. This adaptability can also be achieved, in principle, through other weaker interactions, such as hydrogen bonding. Recently, a noticeable trend has emerged, highlighting the convenient use of self-assembly-driven processes for hydrogel formation. However, utilizing covalent bonds offers two specific benefits [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 67" title="Liao J-X, Huang J-H, Wang T, Sun W-X, Tong Z. Rapid shape memory and pH-modulated spontaneous actuation of dopamine containing hydrogels. Chin J Polym Sci. 2017;35(10):1297–306. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s10118-017-1991-9&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR67" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1421">67</a>]. First, the network remains covalently linked, providing enhanced stability against minor environmental changes like temperature fluctuations [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 68" title="Zheng N, Xu Y, Zhao Q, Xie T. Dynamic covalent polymer networks: a molecular platform for designing functions beyond chemical recycling and self-healing. Chem Rev. 2021;121(3):1716–45. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.chemrev.0c00938&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR68" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1424">68</a>]. Additionally, exchange reactions, such as those between amines and imines, are often kinetically regulated by catalysts, allowing control over the network’s structure and the option to stabilize it by slowing reaction kinetics as needed. Reversible bonds can be incorporated along the polymer backbone or positioned at the crosslink sites [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 69" title="Wang P, Deng G, Zhou L, Li Z, Chen Y. Ultrastretchable, self-healable hydrogels based on dynamic covalent bonding and triblock copolymer micellization. ACS Macro Lett. 2017;6(8):881–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsmacrolett.7b00519&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR69" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1427">69</a>]. Upon exposure to an external trigger, the network can break either at the crosslinking points or along the backbone, leading to network fragments with varied chemical compositions. In both scenarios, any encapsulated molecules are subsequently released. This release occurs as the polymer chains dissolve, losing their ability to retain the load. In drug delivery applications, this mechanism enables controlled release rates governed by the kinetics of network degradation, which depend on the reversible bond dynamics [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 70" title="Kamaly N, Yameen B, Wu J, Farokhzad OC. Degradable controlled-release polymers and polymeric nanoparticles: mechanisms of controlling drug release. Chem Rev. 2016;116(4):2602–63. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.chemrev.5b00346&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR70" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1430">70</a>].</p><p>One notable example is based on catechol chemistry, where a hydrogel containing di-methyl acrylamide (DMA) units can be reversibly crosslinked via complexation with Fe<sup>3+</sup> ions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 67" title="Liao J-X, Huang J-H, Wang T, Sun W-X, Tong Z. Rapid shape memory and pH-modulated spontaneous actuation of dopamine containing hydrogels. Chin J Polym Sci. 2017;35(10):1297–306. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s10118-017-1991-9&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR67" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1439">67</a>]. Here, reversibility is achieved by modulating between tri- and mono-chelate complexes, responsive to the solution’s pH. The resulting material exhibits a shape memory effect activated by pH fluctuations. To induce sol–gel transitions and potentially self-healing properties in response to various stimuli, different functional groups-such as disulfide and acylhydrazone-can be integrated along the backbone, as illustrated in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig4">4</a> [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 71" title="Yu F, Cao X, Du J, Wang G, Chen X. Multifunctional hydrogel with good structure integrity, self-healing, and tissue-adhesive property formed by combining diels-alder click reaction and acylhydrazone bond. ACS Appl Mater Interfaces. 2015;7(43):24023–31. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsami.5b06896&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR71" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1445">71</a>].</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-4" data-title="Fig. 4"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig4" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 4</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig4_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-4-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig4_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 4" loading="lazy" width="685" height="793"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/4" data-track-dest="link:Figure4 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 4" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div><p class="c-article-section__figure-credit text-right c-article-section__figure-credit-right" data-test="figure-credit">Adapted with permission from ref. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 71" title="Yu F, Cao X, Du J, Wang G, Chen X. Multifunctional hydrogel with good structure integrity, self-healing, and tissue-adhesive property formed by combining diels-alder click reaction and acylhydrazone bond. ACS Appl Mater Interfaces. 2015;7(43):24023–31. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsami.5b06896&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR71" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1469">71</a>]. Copyright 2015 American Chemical Society</p></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-4-desc"><p> <b>a</b> Illustration of the dual crosslinking process and (<b>b</b>) Gelation characteristics of the dual crosslinked hydrogel. </p></div></div></figure></div><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec9"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">4.2 </span>Chemically crosslinked hydrogels</h3><p>Covalent bonds play a crucial role in polymer chemistry, particularly in chemical crosslinking where polymers are joined through covalent interactions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 72" title="Maeda T, Otsuka H, Takahara A. Dynamic covalent polymers: reorganizable polymers with dynamic covalent bonds. Prog Polym Sci. 2009;34(7):581–604." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR72" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1489">72</a>]. These bonds offer superior mechanical stability compared to non-covalent interactions. Chemical crosslinking methods encompass a range of techniques, including radical polymerization, chemical reactions involving complementary groups, high-energy irradiation, and enzymatic processes. Unlike physical crosslinking, chemical crosslinking necessitates the use of a crosslinking agent capable of reacting with other materials (Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig5">5</a>) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 73" title="Tillet G, Boutevin B, Ameduri B. Chemical reactions of polymer crosslinking and post-crosslinking at room and medium temperature. Prog Polym Sci. 2011;36(2):191–217." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR73" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1495">73</a>]. Hydrogels, for instance, are chemically crosslinked through various methods such as chain-growth polymerization involving addition and condensation polymerization, gamma and electron beam polymerization [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 74" title="Bashir S, Hina M, Iqbal J, Rajpar AH, Mujtaba MA, Alghamdi NA, Wageh S, Ramesh K, Ramesh S. Fundamental concepts of hydrogels: synthesis, properties, and their applications. Polymers. 2020;12(11):2702." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR74" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1498">74</a>]. Within chain-growth polymerization, different approaches like free radical polymerization, controlled free radical polymerization, anionic, and cationic polymerization are employed, each involving initiation, propagation, and termination processes [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 75" title="Matyjaszewski K, Spanswick J. Controlled/living radical polymerization. In: Handbook of polymer synthesis. New York: CRC Press; 2004. p. 907–54." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR75" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1501">75</a>]. These methods collectively contribute to the diverse landscape of chemical crosslinking in polymer science.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-5" data-title="Fig. 5"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig5" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 5</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig5_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-5-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig5_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 5" loading="lazy" width="685" height="325"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/5" data-track-dest="link:Figure5 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 5" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-5-desc"><p>Schematic representation of chemical crosslinking</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Following initiation, a free radical active site emerges, initiating the addition of monomers in a chain-like fashion. The synthesis of hydrogels using poly(<i>N</i>-isopropyl acrylamide) follows conventional free radical polymerization techniques [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 76" title="Dharmasiri MB, Mudiyanselage TK. Thermo-responsive poly (N-isopropyl acrylamide) hydrogel with increased response rate. Polym Bull. 2021;78:3183–98." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR76" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1528">76</a>]. Similarly, hydrogels based on polyvinyl alcohol (PVA) are produced through free radical copolymerization. Utilizing benzoyl peroxide as a reaction initiator and ethylene glycol dimethacrylate as a cross-linking agent, PVA can be chemically cross-linked with monomer methacrylic acid in an aqueous environment, thus conferring pH-sensitive properties [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 77" title="Velazco-Medel MA, Camacho-Cruz LA, Bucio E. Modification of PDMS with acrylic acid and acrylic acid/ethylene glycol dimethacrylate by simultaneous polymerization assisted by gamma radiation. Radiat Phys Chem. 2020;171: 108754." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR77" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1531">77</a>]. Such chemically cross-linked PVA hydrogels show promise in efficiently delivering 5-fluorouracil to the colon for treating colorectal cancer [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 78" title="Arévalo-Pérez R, Maderuelo C, Lanao JM. Recent advances in colon drug delivery systems. J Control Release. 2020;327:703–24." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR78" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1534">78</a>].</p><p>Controlled radical polymerizations provide a distinct advantage over free radical polymerizations by prolonging chain longevity, particularly for macromolecular engineering applications [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 79" title="Matyjaszewski K, Tsarevsky NV. Macromolecular engineering by atom transfer radical polymerization. J Am Chem Soc. 2014;136(18):6513–33." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR79" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1540">79</a>]. In polymeric hydrogel synthesis, the utilization of cationic or anionic polymerization techniques is avoided due to their vulnerability to aquatic environments. To achieve condensation and addition reactions, polyfunctional crosslinking agents containing monomer functional groups are introduced sequentially during polymerization. Among these agents is Tetramethylethylenediamine, which can convert water-soluble monomers into hydrogels [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 13" title="Zhao X, Chen X, Yuk H, Lin S, Liu X, Parada G. Soft materials by design: unconventional polymer networks give extreme properties. Chem Rev. 2021;121(8):4309–72." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR13" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1543">13</a>]. Upon exposure to water, polymer chains crosslink, resulting in the formation of the hydrogel structure. The unique surface characteristics of hydrogel are attributed to the filling of network gaps by water molecules. Gamma and electron beam polymerization processes utilize high-energy electromagnetic radiation as crosslinkers, eliminating the necessity for crosslinking agents [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 80" title="Maitra J, Shukla VK. Cross-linking in hydrogels—a review. Am J Polym Sci. 2014;4(2):25–31." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR80" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1546">80</a>]. Irradiation of monomer aqueous solutions induce polymerization, leading to hydrogel formation without the use of hazardous crosslinking chemicals.</p><p>During gamma and electron beam polymerizations, the initiation, propagation, and termination phases typical of free radical polymerization are observed. Vinyl monomers undergo hydroxyl radical formation, initiating rapid free radical polymerization within the polymer chain. Upon reaching the critical gelation point, hydrogel formation ensues. This method offers the advantage of operating under physiological pH and room temperature conditions without the requirement for hazardous crosslinking chemicals such as potassium persulfate, as in conventional techniques [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 81" title="Alavarse AC, Frachini ECG, da Silva RLCG, Lima VH, Shavandi A, Petri DFS. Crosslinkers for polysaccharides and proteins: synthesis conditions, mechanisms, and crosslinking efficiency, a review. Int J Biol Macromol. 2022;202:558–96." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR81" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e1552">81</a>] (Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Tab1">1</a>).</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-1"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab1" data-test="table-caption">Table 1 Representation of various crosslinking techniques for different hydrogels with their various properties</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/tables/1" aria-label="Full size table 1"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div></div></div></section><section data-title="Self-healing properties"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec10-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec10"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">5 </span>Self-healing properties</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec10-content"><p>Reversible, non-covalent, and dynamic covalent interactions are pervasive in nature, playing key roles in many biological and physical processes [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 93" title="Webber MJ, Tibbitt MW. Dynamic and reconfigurable materials from reversible network interactions. Nat Rev Mater. 2022;7(7):541–56. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1038/s41578-021-00412-x&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR93" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2350">93</a>]. Advanced force measurement techniques, including Surface Force Apparatus, Atomic Force Microscopy, and other nanomechanical methods, provide detailed quantitative insights into these interactions, helping to explain natural phenomena at a fundamental level [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 94" title="Müller DJ, Dumitru AC, Lo Giudice C, Gaub HE, Hinterdorfer P, Hummer G, De Yoreo JJ, Dufrêne YF, Alsteens D. Atomic force microscopy-based force spectroscopy and multiparametric imaging of biomolecular and cellular systems. Chem Rev. 2021;121(19):11701–25. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.chemrev.0c00617&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR94" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2353">94</a>]. By integrating reversible crosslinking elements into hydrogel networks, researchers have developed self-healing hydrogels with promising applications in biomedical, electrical, and engineering fields [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 95" title="Talebian S, Mehrali M, Taebnia N, Pennisi CP, Kadumudi FB, Foroughi J, Hasany M, Nikkhah M, Akbari M, Orive G, et al. Self-healing hydrogels: the next paradigm shift in tissue engineering? Advanced Science. 2019;6(16):1801664. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/advs.201801664&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR95" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2356">95</a>]. Hydrogels that rely on hydrogen bonding are often sensitive to water; however, strategies like complementary hydrogen bonds and protective hydrophobic pockets effectively address this limitation. Ionic interactions offer versatile bonding-ranging from robust, permanent connections to weak, reversible ones-depending on the interacting ions and surrounding conditions. Inspired by marine mussels, the catechol-Fe<sup>3+</sup> coordination represents a notable example of reversible metal–ligand coordination and is frequently utilized in self-healing hydrogel designs [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 96" title="Zeng H, Hwang DS, Israelachvili JN, Waite JH. Strong reversible Fe3+-mediated bridging between dopa-containing protein films in water. Proc Natl Acad Sci. 2010;107(29):12850–3. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1007416107&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR96" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2361">96</a>]. Investigations into newer interactions, such as cation-π and anion-π interactions, have spurred innovation in the development of novel self-healing hydrogels.</p><p>Ionic interactions, or electrostatic attractions between charged species, are another common crosslinking approach in hydrogel synthesis [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 97" title="Bashir S, Hina M, Iqbal J, Rajpar AH, Mujtaba MA, Alghamdi NA, Wageh S, Ramesh K, Ramesh S. Fundamental concepts of hydrogels: synthesis, properties, and their applications. Polymers. 2020;12:2702." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR97" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2367">97</a>]. This often involves interactions between charged polymer chains and polymers or ions of opposite charge. The strength and durability of these bonds can significantly vary depending on the nature of the ions and interaction conditions. Strong ionic bonds can form stable, durable connections similar to covalent bonds, while weaker ionic bonds are more flexible and reversible, imparting self-healing properties to the hydrogel network [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 98" title="Zhu M, He S, Dai Y, Han J, Gan L, Liu J, Long M. Long-lasting sustainable self-healing ion gel with triple-network by trigger-free dynamic hydrogen bonds and ion bonds. ACS Sustain Chem Eng. 2018;6(12):17087–98. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acssuschemeng.8b04452&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR98" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2370">98</a>]. By adjusting the chemical structures of the polyelectrolyte pairs, researchers have converted a weak, highly extensible hydrogel (fracture stress of 0.03 MPa and stretchability up to 3500%) based on sodium 2-acrylamido-2-methylpropanesulfonate and 3-(methacryloylamino)propyl trimethylammonium chloride (MPTC) to a much stronger and stiffer hydrogel (5.4 MPa, 750%) using MPTC and sodium <i>p</i>-styrenesulfonate (NaSS) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 99" title="Hai M, Zhang Q, Li Z, Cheng M, Kuehne AJC, Shi F. Visualizing polymer diffusion in hydrogel self-healing. Supramol Mater. 2022;1: 100009. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.supmat.2022.100009&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR99" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2376">99</a>]. A vital step in developing such polyelectrolyte-based hydrogels is dialysis, which helps to reduce counterion shielding that may weaken interactions. Generally, the molecular mobility in strong, tough hydrogels is restricted. Studies have shown that hydrogels with softness below a specific threshold, quantified by their elastic modulus, can undergo self-healing. Therefore, softening of the fractured surfaces is typically necessary for these types of hydrogels. This can be achieved by immersing the hydrogel in high-salt solutions, which competitively bind with the charged groups, disrupting ionic crosslinks. The PMPTC/PNaSS hydrogel, for example, demonstrated a 66% healing efficiency after soaking the cut surfaces in 3M NaCl solution for two minutes, followed by a 12-h healing period. Combining strong and weak ionic bonds within a single system can produce self-healing hydrogels that balance both extensibility and strength. For instance, a highly stretchable and durable hydrogel was recently developed using a mix of strong amino/carboxyl and weak quaternary ammonium/carboxyl bonds between functionalized polymers and carbon nanotubes [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 100" title="Wu M, Pan M, Qiao C, Ma Y, Yan B, Yang W, Peng Q, Han L, Zeng H. Ultra stretchable, tough, elastic and transparent hydrogel skins integrated with intelligent sensing functions enabled by machine learning algorithms. Chem Eng J. 2022;450: 138212. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cej.2022.138212&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR100" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2379">100</a>]. In this system, strong ionic bonds provide stable crosslinks, while weaker interactions act as reversible sacrificial bonds, dissipating energy under stress. This hydrogel’s ionic conductivity enables its application as a strain or pressure sensor capable of detecting subtle human motions. When integrated with machine learning algorithms, the sensor successfully recognized human handwriting.</p><p>Hydrogels linked through dynamic covalent interactions show particular potential for biomedical uses, as they can often be synthesized from natural polymers and exhibit gelation and self-healing properties under specific pH conditions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 101" title="Zhang Y, Qi Y, Ulrich S, Barboiu M, Ramström O. Dynamic covalent polymers for biomedical applications. Mater Chem Front. 2020;4(2):489–506. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1039/C9QM00598F&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR101" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2385">101</a>]. For instance, imine-based hydrogels form easily and exhibit self-repairing behavior in neutral environments, while hydrazone bonds may require catalytic assistance due to kinetic stability at neutral pH [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 95" title="Talebian S, Mehrali M, Taebnia N, Pennisi CP, Kadumudi FB, Foroughi J, Hasany M, Nikkhah M, Akbari M, Orive G, et al. Self-healing hydrogels: the next paradigm shift in tissue engineering? Advanced Science. 2019;6(16):1801664. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/advs.201801664&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR95" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2388">95</a>]. Boronic ester-based hydrogels are responsive to glucose, and those with disulfide bonds exhibit light- and redox-sensitivity.</p><p>The imine bond (–N=CH–), also known as Schiff base, is a dynamic linkage formed through the condensation reaction of aldehydes with primary amines [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 102" title="Liu X, Manzur C, Novoa N, Celedón S, Carrillo D, Hamon J-R. Multidentate unsymmetrically-substituted Schiff bases and their metal complexes: synthesis, functional materials properties, and applications to catalysis. Coord Chem Rev. 2018;357:144–72. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ccr.2017.11.030&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR102" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2394">102</a>]. This process occurs mildly acidic to basic conditions, with strong acidity favoring hydrolysis of the bond. Because of its reversible hydrolysis and exchange reactions in mildly acidic or basic environments, the imine bond displays pH-dependent flexibility and reversibility, making it a valuable choice for fabricating self-healing hydrogels, especially for medical applications. The pH-responsiveness and reversibility of this bond have been effectively quantified at the nanoscale. Biomacromolecules containing amine groups, such as chitosan and gelatin, are critical in forming imine-based hydrogels [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 103" title="Yang H, Fustin C-A. Design and applications of dynamic hydrogels based on reversible C═N bonds. Macromol Chem Phys. 2023;224(20):2300211. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/macp.202300211&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR103" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2397">103</a>]. They can be readily crosslinked with aldehyde-functionalized oxidized polysaccharides or difunctional benzaldehyde-modified PEG, resulting in self-healing, biocompatible, and biodegradable gels suitable for applications like drug and cell delivery, wound repair, and tissue regeneration. Particularly, the pH-sensitive nature of these hydrogels makes them suitable for targeted drug delivery in acidic regions, such as tumors, wounds, or infected areas. The pH-responsiveness of these hydrogels correlates with the pKa of the amine groups involved. Wu et al., achieved highly sensitive, pH-regulated drug release in the acidosis range of 6.4–7.4 by using amino-functionalized silica nanoparticles with a moderate pKa around 7.6, combined with an aldehyde-modified, superhydrophilic zwitterionic polymer (Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig6">6</a>) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 104" title="Wu M, Han L, Yan B, Zeng H. Self-healing hydrogels based on reversible noncovalent and dynamic covalent interactions: a short review. Supramol Mater. 2023;2: 100045. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.supmat.2023.100045&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR104" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2403">104</a>]. In another case, incorporating an imine bond within PAM hydrogel networks resulted in a self-healing and robust material [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 105" title="Pourjavadi A, Tavakolizadeh M, Hosseini SH, Rabiee N, Bagherzadeh M. Highly stretchable, self-adhesive, and self-healable double network hydrogel based on alginate/polyacrylamide with tunable mechanical properties. J Polym Sci. 2020;58(15):2062–73. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/pol.20200295&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR105" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2406">105</a>]. A noteworthy property, strain-stiffening, was observed in an imine-crosslinked PEG/polyethylenimine (PEI) hydrogel, which enhances the hydrogel's ability to withstand repeated stress and promotes its self-healing capability.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-6" data-title="Fig. 6"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig6" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 6</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig6_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-6-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig6_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 6" loading="lazy" width="685" height="708"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/6" data-track-dest="link:Figure6 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 6" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-6-desc"><p>Self-healing hydrogels facilitated by dynamic covalent interactions. <b>a</b> A Schiff base-crosslinked hydrogel exhibiting remarkable pH sensitivity, particularly in the mildly acidic range. <b>b</b> A self-repairing, strain-enhancing hydrogel created through the Schiff base reaction between branched PEI and dialdehyde-functionalized PEO. <b>c</b> A boronic ester-based hydrogel with superior self-healing capabilities activated by near-infrared light. <b>d</b> A dynamic hydrogel formed through hydrazone and disulfide linkages, displaying pH-responsive self-healing properties. Reproduced with permission from ref. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 103" title="Yang H, Fustin C-A. Design and applications of dynamic hydrogels based on reversible C═N bonds. Macromol Chem Phys. 2023;224(20):2300211. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/macp.202300211&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR103" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2432">103</a>]. This study is under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License, which permits use, sharing, adaptation, distribution, and reproduction in any medium or format, as long as you give appropriate credit to the original author(s) and the source as well as provide a link to the Creative Commons license (<a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/</a>, accessed on 19 October 2023)</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Despite significant progress in developing self-healing hydrogels, several challenges remain. Enhancing the mechanical properties of self-healing hydrogels is often constrained by the limited mobility of molecular chains, and achieving efficient self-repair may require additional treatments, such as applying saline solutions or organic solvents, or allowing long recovery times [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 106" title="Rumon MMH, Akib AA, Sultana F, Moniruzzaman M, Niloy MS, Shakil MS, Roy CK. Self-healing hydrogels: development, biomedical applications, and challenges. Polymers (Basel). 2022;14(21):4539. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/polym14214539&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR106" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2455">106</a>]. While external stimuli like near-infrared (NIR) light can enhance self-healing, hydrogels with both high mechanical strength and autonomous self-healing remain rare. In biological systems, multiple interaction mechanisms, such as hydrogen bonding, metal coordination, π-interactions, and chemical bonding, often work together to support complex processes like mussel adhesion and protein folding [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 107" title="Geng H, Zhang P, Peng Q, Cui J, Hao J, Zeng H. Principles of Cation−π interactions for engineering mussel-inspired functional materials. Acc Chem Res. 2022;55(8):1171–82. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.2c00068&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR107" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2458">107</a>]. By mimicking this multi-mechanism approach, self-healing hydrogels with improved functionalities can be created. Furthermore, the development of smart, stimuli-responsive self-healing hydrogels remains an exciting avenue, as improved precision in controlling response conditions and timing is increasingly needed for next-generation intelligent materials. Fundamental studies of the interaction mechanisms that drive self-healing behavior are essential to further this field, advancing both theoretical understanding and practical applications.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Biodegradability"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec11-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec11"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">6 </span>Biodegradability</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec11-content"><p>Biopolymer-derived hydrogels provide substantial advantages in biological and environmental applications due to their natural propensity for degradation [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 108" title="Das A, Ringu T, Ghosh S, Pramanik N. A comprehensive review on recent advances in preparation, physicochemical characterization, and bioengineering applications of biopolymers. Polym Bull. 2023;80(7):7247–312. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s00289-022-04443-4&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR108" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2470">108</a>]. Biodegradability refers to the process by which materials undergo breakdown through chemical reactions facilitated by microorganisms or enzymes, ultimately resulting in the transformation into simpler compounds within a defined period. To optimize the performance and reduce the negative impacts of polysaccharide-based hydrogels, it is crucial to understand the various factors and mechanisms that influence biodegradation rates. The degradation rate is notably impacted by several factors, including the degree of polymer cross-linking, chemical composition, functional group variations, and environmental conditions such as temperature, pressure, pH, and the presence of microbial or enzymatic activity [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 109" title="Liu L, Xu M, Ye Y, Zhang B. On the degradation of (micro)plastics: degradation methods, influencing factors, environmental impacts. Sci Total Environ. 2022;806: 151312. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2021.151312&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR109" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2473">109</a>].</p><p>For biopolymer-based hydrogels, the biodegradation process spans a wide range of time scales, from a few days to several months, and in some cases, it may take years [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 110" title="Vinod A, Sanjay MR, Suchart S, Jyotishkumar P. Renewable and sustainable biobased materials: an assessment on biofibers, biofilms, biopolymers and biocomposites. J Clean Prod. 2020;258: 120978. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jclepro.2020.120978&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR110" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2479">110</a>]. The degradation rate is also closely linked to the polymer's chemical structure. For example, chitosan, a derivative of the chitin biopolymer, is a well-researched polysaccharide whose degradation rate typically ranges from several weeks to months [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 111" title="Kakoria A, Sinha-Ray S. A review on biopolymer-based fibers via electrospinning and solution blowing and their applications. Fibers. 2018;6:45." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR111" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2482">111</a>]. The breakdown of chitosan is primarily governed by factors such as polymer molecular weight and the extent of cross-linking, with the degree of deacetylation also playing a role. Similarly, hydrogels made from alginate, derived from seaweed, undergo decomposition within weeks to months under physiological conditions. Hyaluronic acid-based hydrogels degrade relatively quickly, within a few days to one week, while cellulose-based hydrogels tend to break down over a period of months to a year [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 112" title="Tomić SL, Babić Radić MM, Vuković JS, Filipović VV, Nikodinovic-Runic J, Vukomanović M. Alginate-based hydrogels and scaffolds for biomedical applications. Mar Drugs. 2023;21:177." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR112" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2485">112</a>].</p><p>The biodegradability of these hydrogels must be controlled to enhance their utility across various applications. Several approaches can influence the rate of decomposition, including modifications to the polymer’s chemical structure, such as cross-linking, grafting, or the incorporation of active functional groups [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 113" title="Bhattacharya A, Misra BN. Grafting: a versatile means to modify polymers: techniques, factors and applications. Prog Polym Sci. 2004;29(8):767–814. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.progpolymsci.2004.05.002&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR113" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2491">113</a>]. Increasing cross-linking typically extends the degradation period by reducing enzyme or microorganism accessibility and limiting water absorption [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 114" title="Bian H, Cao M, Wen H, Tan Z, Jia S, Cui J. Biodegradation of polyvinyl alcohol using cross-linked enzyme aggregates of degrading enzymes from Bacillus niacini. Int J Biol Macromol. 2019;124:10–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2018.11.204&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR114" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2494">114</a>]. In contrast, incorporating hydrolytically sensitive or enzymatically cleavable bonds can accelerate the breakdown process. Additionally, environmental factors such as temperature, pressure, pH, and the concentration of active enzymes or microorganisms can substantially affect degradation rates. By manipulating these physiological conditions, it is possible to control the degradation speed of polysaccharide-based hydrogels in specific contexts. For instance, pH-responsive hydrogels can be engineered to degrade more rapidly under the acidic conditions found in inflamed tissues.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Biomedical applications of hydrogels"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec12-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec12"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7 </span>Biomedical applications of hydrogels</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec12-content"><p>Mechanically robust hydrogels represent a coveted asset in biomedical spheres owing to their inherent behaviors, including large water content, pliability, softness, and live tissue compatibility. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 115" title="Baniasadi H, Abidnejad R, Fazeli M, Lipponen J, Niskanen J, Kontturi E, Seppälä J, Rojas OJ. Innovations in hydrogel-based manufacturing: a comprehensive review of direct ink writing technique for biomedical applications. Adv Colloid Interface Sci. 2024;2024:103095." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR115" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2505">115</a>] Synthesized through either physically crosslinked or chemically cross-linked of hydrophilic networks, these gels encompass a spectrum of natural and synthetic variations. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 116" title="Varaprasad K, Raghavendra GM, Jayaramudu T, Yallapu MM, Sadiku R. A mini review on hydrogels classification and recent developments in miscellaneous applications. Mater Sci Eng C. 2017;79:958–71." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR116" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2508">116</a>] Their biomimetic nature renders them exceptionally promising for myriad biomedical endeavors [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 117" title="Arif ZU, Khalid MY, Noroozi R, Hossain M, Shi HH, Tariq A, Ramakrishna S, Umer R. Additive manufacturing of sustainable biomaterials for biomedical applications. Asian J Pharm Sci. 2023;18(3): 100812. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ajps.2023.100812&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR117" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2511">117</a>]. Recently, hydrogels are integral to diverse fields including contact lens production, diabetic-wound care, drug carrier, artificial tissue engineering, and hygiene products [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 118" title="Jacob S, Nair AB, Shah J, Sreeharsha N, Gupta S, Shinu P. Emerging role of hydrogels in drug delivery systems, tissue engineering and wound management. Pharmaceutics. 2021;13(3):357." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR118" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2514">118</a>].</p><p>This review undertakes a thorough examination of hydrogels, delving into their key attributes and biological utilities. Beginning with the seminal contributions of Wicht Erle to the latest strides in hydrogel technology, it offers readers a comprehensive grasp of the subject [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 119" title="Raina N, Pahwa R, Bhattacharya J, Paul AK, Nissapatorn V, de Lourdes Pereira M, Oliveira SMR, Dolma KG, Rahmatullah M, Wilairatana P, et al. Drug delivery strategies and biomedical significance of hydrogels: translational considerations. Pharmaceutics. 2022;14:574." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR119" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2520">119</a>]. Emphasizing tissue and organoid science, drug carriers, wound treatment, and soft robotics, this review elucidates the current landscape and future trajectories of these applications, providing valuable insights into ongoing research and product development [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 16" title="Correa S, Grosskopf AK, Lopez Hernandez H, Chan D, Yu AC, Stapleton LM, Appel EA. Translational applications of hydrogels. Chem Rev. 2021;121(18):11385–457. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.chemrev.0c01177&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR16" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2523">16</a>].</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec13"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.1 </span>Hydrogels in tissue engineering</h3><p>A multitude of patients confront the daunting prospect of organ or tissue loss due to accidents or illnesses, underscoring the urgent demand for effective treatments. Although tissue and organ transplants are established therapies, their efficacy is hampered by the persistent shortage of donors. The concept of "tissue engineering," initially proposed in 1988, merges principles from engineering and life sciences to comprehend the intricate connection between structure and function in mammalian tissues [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 120" title="Brown RA. Extreme tissue engineering: concepts and strategies for tissue fabrication. New York: Wiley; 2013." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR120" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2533">120</a>]. Its primary objective is to cultivate biological substitutes capable of repairing and regenerating damaged tissues or organs.</p><p>Hydrogels have emerged as crucial components within tissue engineering, offering remarkable versatility across diverse applications [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 121" title="Gomez-Florit M, Pardo A, Domingues RMA, Graça AL, Babo PS, Reis RL, Gomes ME. Natural-based hydrogels for tissue engineering applications. Molecules. 2020;25(24):5858." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR121" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2539">121</a>]. They function adeptly as space-fillers, carriers for bioactive substances, and creators of complex three-dimensional structures conducive to cell organization and targeted tissue development. Among their various applications, hydrogel-based space-filling agents, acting as scaffolds, fulfill a range of roles including bulk augmentation, prevention of adhesions, and functioning as biological adhesives [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 122" title="Cascone S, Lamberti G. Hydrogel-based commercial products for biomedical applications: a review. Int J Pharm. 2020;573: 118803." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR122" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2542">122</a>]. Notably, hydrogel scaffolds excel in tasks such as drug delivery, promotion of angiogenesis, encapsulation of secretory cells, and facilitation of cell transplantation in tissue engineering projects [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 123" title="Atienza Roca P. Development of hydrogel-based strategies for tissue vascularisation. 2021." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR123" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2545">123</a>]. The key feature of biocompatibility ensures that hydrogels can integrate with bodily organs without causing damage to surround tissues or eliciting adverse reactions.</p><p>Both synthetic and naturally derived polymers contribute to the array of materials suitable for hydrogel formation in tissue engineering [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Arif ZU, Khalid MY, Noroozi R, Sadeghianmaryan A, Jalalvand M, Hossain M. Recent advances in 3D-printed polylactide and polycaprolactone-based biomaterials for tissue engineering applications. Int J Biol Macromol. 2022;218:930–68. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2022.07.140&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="#ref-CR124" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2551">124</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Bozkurt Y, Karayel E. 3D printing technology; methods, biomedical applications, future opportunities and trends. J Market Res. 2021;14:1430–50. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmrt.2021.07.050&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="#ref-CR125" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2551_1">125</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" title="Khalid MY, Arif ZU, Al Rashid A, Bukhari SMZS, Hossain M, Koç M. Shape-memory and self-healing properties of sustainable cellulosic nanofibers-based hybrid materials for novel applications. Giant. 2024;19: 100299. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.giant.2024.100299&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="#ref-CR126" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2551_2">126</a>,<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 127" title="Khalid MY, Arif ZU, Noroozi R, Hossain M, Ramakrishna S, Umer R. 3D/4D printing of cellulose nanocrystals-based biomaterials: additives for sustainable applications. Int J Biol Macromol. 2023;251: 126287. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2023.126287&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR127" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2554">127</a>]. Synthetic options like PEO, PVA, PAA, and polypeptides offer tailored properties for specific applications [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 128" title="Mota C, Camarero-Espinosa S, Baker MB, Wieringa P, Moroni L. Bioprinting: from tissue and organ development to in vitro models. Chem Rev. 2020;120(19):10547–607." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR128" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2557">128</a>]. Meanwhile, naturally sourced polysaccharide such as alginate, hyaluronic acid, agarose, fibrin, gelatin, chitosan, and collagen, provide biologically relevant matrices for tissue engineering endeavors [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 129" title="Wani SUD, Gautam SP, Qadrie ZL, Gangadharappa HV. Silk fibroin as a natural polymeric based bio-material for tissue engineering and drug delivery systems—a review. Int J Biol Macromol. 2020;163:2145–61." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR129" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2560">129</a>].</p><p>The nano and microparticles based composite hydrogel are useful as a biodegradable, self-assembly network system. These microparticles, composed of cross-linked polysaccharide such as collagen and potentially carrying biologically reactive substances, offer a promising avenue for enhancing mechanically robust hydrogels in biomedical applications [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 130" title="Reddy N, Reddy R, Jiang Q. Crosslinking biopolymers for biomedical applications. Trends Biotechnol. 2015;33(6):362–9." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR130" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2566">130</a>]. Figure <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig7">7</a> represents various real-world applications.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-7" data-title="Fig. 7"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig7" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 7</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig7_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-7-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig7_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 7" loading="lazy" width="685" height="410"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/7" data-track-dest="link:Figure7 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 7" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-7-desc"><p>Schematic image of hydrogels for real-world applications</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The novel technique introduced involves the creation of super-absorbent semi-solid hydrogel microparticles [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 131" title="Caló E, Khutoryanskiy VV. Biomedical applications of hydrogels: a review of patents and commercial products. Eur Polymer J. 2015;65:252–67." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR131" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2593">131</a>]. These microparticles possess the unique ability to swell in water without transitioning into a liquid state. This characteristic is attributed to their defined shape, which is maintained through cross-linking. This method, after undergoing polymerization, results in a scaffold that can be directly utilized for treating skeletal defects without the risk of the hydrogel orogen leaching out. To form these hydrogels, self-assembling peptides are employed, characterized by alternating hydrophobic unit and hydrophilic amino acids units [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 132" title="Chen J, Zou X. Self-assemble peptide biomaterials and their biomedical applications. Bioactive Mater. 2019;4:120–31." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR132" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2596">132</a>]. These peptides easily assemble in a tissue culture medium. The structures that arise can be transplanted surgically or applied to open wounds. Some aspects of scaffolding have been noted to not provide the best conditions for tissue reconstruction. On the other hand, better results have been shown using hybrid materials regarding cell division, migration, and proliferation. Hydrogel scaffolding serves as vital for the formation of cell sheets and tissues. Future tissue engineering challenges include encouraging blood vessel network creation. This is necessary for tissue nutrition [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 133" title="Kickelbick G. Introduction to hybrid materials. Hybrid Mater. 2007;1:2." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR133" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2599">133</a>]. Hydrogels offer a potential approach for effectively distribute cells of the endothelium and angiogenic agents in targeted zones, hence regulating the vascularization process. Moreover, many tissue types-like bone, muscle, or blood vessels-need superior mechanical qualities that are often lacking in contemporary gels. Thus, future research should explore novel approaches to enhance mechanical properties and achieve better results.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec14"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.2 </span>Hydrogels in wound treatment</h3><p>A wound is a break or defect that can result from trauma or medical conditions. Wounds are categorized based on how many layers of skin they affect. If only the epidermis is damaged, it's a superficial wound. When both the epidermis and dermis are affected, it is called a partial thickness wound. If the wound extends deeper, damaging subcutaneous fat and underlying tissues, it is a full-thickness wound [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 134" title="Aulton ME. Aulton's pharmaceutics: the design and manufacture of medicines. Churchill Livingstone, 2007." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR134" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2610">134</a>]. Wounds are also categorized into acute and chronic types. Chronic wound care is a significant expense for healthcare systems. Effective dressings call for information of the recovery approach, the particulars of the patient, and the effects of various materials [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 134" title="Aulton ME. Aulton's pharmaceutics: the design and manufacture of medicines. Churchill Livingstone, 2007." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR134" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2613">134</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 135" title="Madaghiele M, Demitri C, Sannino A, Ambrosio L. Polymeric hydrogels for burn wound care: advanced skin wound dressings and regenerative templates. Burns Trauma. 2014;2(4):153–61. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.4103/2321-3868.143616&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR135" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2616">135</a>].</p><p>Various factors can impede wound healing, such as dryness, bacterial presence, infection, pressure, moisture buildup, dead tissue, trauma, and swelling [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 136" title="Jones V, Grey JE, Harding K. ABC of wound healing wound dressings. BMJ. 2006;332:777–80. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.332.7544.777&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR136" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2622">136</a>]. An effective wound management product needs to handle several key functions. It should absorb extra fluids and toxins, keep the wound adequately moist, shield it from infections, prevent overheating, and remain sterile. Additionally, it must allow air to flow through and be easy to remove without causing more damage. Selecting the appropriate dressing for each type of wound is vital for achieving the best healing results and ensuring patient comfort. There are many different wound care products, including low adherent dressings, foam dressings, hydrocolloids, hydrogels, alginates, semi-permeable films, and antimicrobial dressings. While plain gauze remains common in hospitals, recent research in wound dressing has resulted in advanced materials that provide better healing results [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 136" title="Jones V, Grey JE, Harding K. ABC of wound healing wound dressings. BMJ. 2006;332:777–80. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.332.7544.777&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR136" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2625">136</a>].</p><p>Hydrocolloids consist of various compounds including sodium carboxymethylcellulose, gelatin, pectin, elastomers, and adhesives. They serve multiple purposes in wound care such as debridement, maintaining moisture, and forming gels. Unlike some other wound treatments, hydrogels can transform into gels without additional wound fluids, making them suitable for dry wounds. Their ability to donate moisture aids in autolytic debridement, which enhances collagenase production and helps increase the moisture levels in necrotic wounds. By absorbing and retaining contaminated exudate, hydrogels isolate bacteria, detritus, and odor molecules within their gel structure, promoting a cleaner wound environment. Hydrogel dressings, known for their high-water content, are advantageous for treating various wounds such as pressure sores, lacerations, and burns because they promote the passage of vapor and oxygen. In burn care, products like Burn shield are especially effective. These dressings, which consist mostly of water and a small amount of Melaleuca alternifolia extract, offer cooling and keep the wound hydrated [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 137" title="Jones AC, Gosling SD. Temperament and personality in dogs (Canis familiaris): a review and evaluation of past research. Appl Anim Behav Sci. 2005;95(1–2):1–53. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.applanim.2005.04.008&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR137" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2631">137</a>]. They are also utilized for managing granulating cavity wounds.</p><p>Recently, numerous gel products designed for treating diabetic wounds have finished or are in the process of clinical trials. These innovative treatments aim to improve healing for individuals with diabetes, offering new hope and potential advancements in medical care. Researchers are actively working to validate the effectiveness and safety of these gels through rigorous testing. The positive outcomes of these trials could lead to better management and recovery options for diabetic patients [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 138" title="Rosli MA, Nasir NAM, Mustafa MZ, Othman MA, Zakaria Z, Halim AS. Effectiveness of stingless bee (Kelulut) honey versus conventional gel dressing in diabetic wound bed preparation: a randomized controlled trial. J Taibah Univ Med Sci. 2024;19(1):209–19." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR138" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2637">138</a>]. This indicates that hydrogel dressings hold significant potential for treating diabetic wounds. In clinical settings, hydrogel dressings generally show consistent degradation and drug release characteristics [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 139" title="Naghib SM, Amiri S, Mozafari MR. Stimuli-responsive chitosan-based nanocarriers for drug delivery in wound dressing applications: a review. Carbohydr Polym Technol Appl. 2024;7: 100497." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR139" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2640">139</a>]. Differences in wound conditions and surroundings often result in varied responses to treatments. To tackle this issue, numerous studies have explored diverse methods such as utilizing hydrophobic interactions or integrating reversible covalent chemical bonds into hydrogel formulations [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 140" title="Liu J, Du C, Huang W, Lei Y. Injectable smart stimuli-responsive hydrogels: pioneering advancements in biomedical applications. Biomater Sci. 2024;12:8." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR140" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2643">140</a>]. The advancement in technology has resulted in the creation of injectable hydrogel dressings. These dressings have the remarkable ability to react to different triggers like glucose levels, pH balance, ROS, temperature changes, and enzymes. By adapting to these stimuli, hydrogel dressings can effectively manage their breakdown and the release of medication. This capability allows for a customized approach to wound care, ensuring optimal healing conditions for different types of wounds [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 141" title="Bercea M, Lupu A. Recent insights into glucose-responsive concanavalin a-based smart hydrogels for controlled insulin delivery. Gels. 2024;10(4):260." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR141" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2646">141</a>]. Zhipeng et al., developed a antioxidation effect of TA and ROS-responsive phenyl borate ester (PBAE), the TA-conjugated nanoparticles (PPBA-TA NPs) with antibacterial properties, ROS-scavenging behavior, and promoting cell migration behavior was conveniently prepared by mixing TA, phenylboronic acid (PBA). Quaternary ammonium salt (QA) groups functionalized with polyphosphate (PPBA) solutions through a PBAE linker. Then, PPBA-TA nanoparticles were mixed with a PVA solution to make PPBA-TA-PVA hydrogels. These could be injected and would heal on their own shown in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig8">8</a> [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 142" title="Ni Z, Yu H, Wang L, Huang Y, Lu H, Zhou H, Liu Q. Multistage ROS-responsive and natural polyphenol-driven prodrug hydrogels for diabetic wound healing. ACS Appl Mater Interfaces. 2022;14(47):52643–58. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsami.2c15686&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR142" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2653">142</a>].</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-8" data-title="Fig. 8"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig8" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 8</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig8_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-8-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig8_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 8" loading="lazy" width="685" height="527"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/8" data-track-dest="link:Figure8 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 8" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div><p class="c-article-section__figure-credit text-right c-article-section__figure-credit-right" data-test="figure-credit">Reproduced with permission from ref. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 141" title="Bercea M, Lupu A. Recent insights into glucose-responsive concanavalin a-based smart hydrogels for controlled insulin delivery. Gels. 2024;10(4):260." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR141" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2670">141</a>]. Copyright 2022, American Chemical Society</p></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-8-desc"><p>Schematic representation of the construction process and structural design of ROS-responsive hydrogels. Representation of synthesis of ROS-responsive hydrogel PPBA-TA-PVA and its mechanism for alleviating inflammation at diabetic wound sites. </p></div></div></figure></div><p>Accurate assessment of the individual wound environment is crucial for personalized treatment. The hydrogel exhibited a unique behavior where its hydrophobic part separated into tiny phases, becoming insoluble in water yet retaining its ability to swell in water [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 143" title="Gu G, Yang X, Li Y, Guo J, Huang J, Nxumalo EN, Mamba BB, Shao L. Advanced zwitterionic polymeric membranes for diverse applications beyond antifouling. Sep Purif Technol. 2025;356: 129848. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.seppur.2024.129848&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR143" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2686">143</a>]. This property ensured that the composite dressing, by soaking up the wound exudate, could acquire a gel-like texture [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 144" title="Zhang Q, Huang Z, Jiang H, Wu M, Dong Z, Chen C, Chen F, Zhao G, Ma P. “Bamboo-like” strong and tough sodium alginate/polyacrylate hydrogel fiber with directional controlled release for wound healing promotion. Carbohyd Polym. 2025;347: 122761. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.carbpol.2024.122761&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR144" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2689">144</a>]. This prevented it from sticking to the wound surface, thereby reducing the risk of further injury and allowing for less frequent dressing changes. Looking ahead, advancements in wound care will heavily rely on the ongoing demands from both the public and healthcare providers. A crucial challenge lies in tailoring the appropriate wound care approach for each individual patient, a task achievable only by offering the most suitable products. It's imperative to innovate new types of dressings while ensuring that their production costs remain affordable.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec15"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.3 </span>Hydrogels as a drug carrier</h3><p>Several studies investigate how hydrogels can be used for delivering drugs [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 145" title="Akib AA, Rumon MMH, Moniruzzaman M, Kumar Roy C, Chowdury A-N. PLA-PEG diblock copolymer micelle as nanocarrier for anti-obesity drug delivery system. ECS Trans. 2022;107(1):19031. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1149/10701.19031ecst&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR145" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2701">145</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 146" title="Akib AA, Shakil R, Rumon MMH, Roy CK, Chowdhury EH, Chowdhury A-N. Natural and synthetic micelles for the delivery of small molecule drugs, imaging agents and nucleic acids. Curr Pharm Des. 2022;28(17):1389–405." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR146" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2704">146</a>]. However, while there is a lot of research on this topic, only a few of these studies have resulted in actual products that are available on the market. Hydrogels garner significant interest for drug delivery owing to their distinct physiochemical characteristics [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 147" title="Hameed H, Faheem S, Paiva-Santos AC, Sarwar HS, Jamshaid M. A comprehensive review of hydrogel-based drug delivery systems: classification, properties, recent trends, and applications. AAPS PharmSciTech. 2024;25(4):1–27." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR147" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2707">147</a>]. Their high porosity, modifiable by adjusting cross-link density and water affinity, stands out. This porous nature facilitates drug loading and subsequent release. Hydrogels offer several advantages for drug delivery, including sustained release, ensuring a prolonged high local concentration of active drug ingredients [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 148" title="Narayanaswamy R, Torchilin VP. Hydrogels and their applications in targeted drug delivery. In: The road from nanomedicine to precision medicine. 2020, pp. 1117–1150." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR148" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2710">148</a>]. Drug release from hydrogels happens through different methods. These include swelling-controlled, chemically controlled, diffusion-controlled, and stimuli sensitive mechanisms. Among diffusion-controlled systems are reservoir and matrix devices. Reservoir systems, like capsules or spheres, have a core filled with the drug, surrounded by a hydrogel membrane, ensuring a steady release rate over time [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 149" title="Davoodi P, Lee LY, Xu Q, Sunil V, Sun Y, Soh S, Wang C-H. Drug delivery systems for programmed and on-demand release. Adv Drug Deliv Rev. 2018;132:104–38." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR149" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2713">149</a>]. Matrix systems uniformly disperse drugs throughout a hydrogel, releasing them at a rate proportional to the square root of time. Swelling-controlled release devices, on the other hand, disperse drugs within a glassy polymer. This polymer swells when in contact with bio-fluids, helping the drug to diffuse [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 47" title="Hill C, Altgen M, Penttilӓ P, Rautkari L. interaction of water vapour with wood and other hygro-responsive materials. J Mater Sci. 2024;59:7595." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2717">47</a>]. In Case II transport, there are constant release kinetics that don't change over time. This process combines swelling-controlled release with diffusion. The drug moves from areas of high concentration to low concentration through hydrogel. Hydrogel-based dosage forms can be designed in different shapes and sizes depending on how the drug is administered.</p><p>Hydrogels are useful for delivering drugs to treat different health problems when applied to the skin. For instance, Nho et al. developed a hydrogel with PVA or poly(vinylpyrrolidone) to treat atopic dermatitis [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 150" title="Nho Y-C, Lim Y-M, Gwon H-J, Choi E-K. Preparation and characterization of PVA/PVP/glycerin/antibacterial agent hydrogels using γ-irradiation followed by freeze–thawing. Korean J Chem Eng. 2009;26:1675–8." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR150" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2723">150</a>]. This hydrogel is designed to alleviate symptoms of dermatitis by harnessing the healing properties of various medicinal plants such as Houttuynia cordata, elm, celandine, and Canavalia gladiata. The process begins with dissolving poly(vinylpyrrolidone) and poly(vinyl alcohol) in the plant extracts, forming a gel-like substance. Physical cross-links are then introduced through freeze/thaw cycles, followed by chemical cross-linking using gamma, UV, or electron beam radiation to ensure sterility [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 151" title="Wu J, Sheng X, Li L, Liang J, Li Y, Zhao Z, Cui F. Rational design of a multifunctional hydrogel trap for water and fertilizer capture: a review. J Agric Food Chem. 2024;72(31):17176–90. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.jafc.4c03207&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR151" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2726">151</a>]. To enhance its functionality, the hydrogel is supported by a hydrophilic non-woven fabric sheet and an air-permeable polyethylene film. This combination not only provides structural support but also allows for efficient transdermal iontophoretic drug delivery [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 152" title="Abbasi M, Heath B. Iontophoresis and electroporation-assisted microneedles: advancements and therapeutic potentials in transdermal drug delivery. Drug Deliv Transl Res. 2024. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s13346-024-01722-7&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR152" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2729">152</a>]. In one approach, polyurethane hydrogel matrices serve as reservoirs for the drug, created by mixing a prepolymer solution containing an isocyanate-capped oxyalkylene-based prepolymer with water [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 153" title="Zhao F, Fan S, Ghate D, Romanova S, Bronich TK, Zhao S. A hydrogel ionic circuit based high-intensity iontophoresis device for intraocular macromolecule and nanoparticle delivery. Adv Mater. 2022;34(5):2107315. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/adma.202107315&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR153" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2732">153</a>]. Once the organic solvent evaporates, the drug is loaded into the hydrogel matrix. Transdermal iontophoresis, a process involving the movement of ionized drugs through the skin via a weak electric current, facilitates the diffusion of drugs into the dermis and eventually into the systemic circulation [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 154" title="Han J, Choi Y-J, Kang S-K. Synergistic strategies of biomolecular transport technologies in transdermal healthcare systems. Adv Healthc Mater. 2024;13:2401753. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/adhm.202401753&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR154" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2735">154</a>]. Alternatively, hydrogel compositions can passively act as transdermal reservoirs. These hydrogels, characterized by high swelling ratios, flexibility, strength, and transparency, show promise not only as carriers for ocular drug delivery but also in broader applications beyond lenses.</p><p>Advancements in drug delivery systems utilizing hydrogels offer significant potential for enhancing medication administration [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 155" title="Liu Y, Huang J, Li S, Li Z, Chen C, Qu G, Chen K, Teng Y, Ma R, Wu X, et al. Advancements in hydrogel-based drug delivery systems for the treatment of inflammatory bowel disease: a review. Biomater Sci. 2024;12(4):837–62. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1039/D3BM01645E&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR155" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2741">155</a>]. By customizing hydrogels to possess varying degrees of water compatibility and structural features, it becomes feasible to finely regulate the speed at which drugs are released and how they dissolve. Such developments could notably benefit patients with conditions such as diabetes and cancer by improving the delivery of delicate molecules crucial for treatment. Future progress may involve employing hydrogels specifically for administering therapeutic proteins and peptides, further expanding their therapeutic applications.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec16"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.4 </span>Hydrogels in soft robotics</h3><p>Many robots are constructed with stiff components [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 156" title="Rahman Khan MM, Rumon MM. Recent progress on the synthesis, morphological topography, and battery applications of polypyrrole-based nanocomposites. Polymers. 2024;16:3277." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR156" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2752">156</a>]. These machines are crafted to efficiently perform predetermined duties, significantly boosting productivity in industrial sectors and aiding human advancement [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 157" title="Melenbrink N, Werfel J, Menges A. On-site autonomous construction robots: towards unsupervised building. Autom Constr. 2020;119: 103312." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR157" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2755">157</a>]. People have just begun to experiment with using robots in their daily lives. Traditional rigid-body robots, on the other hand, fail to operate in unstructured situations because they are made up of distinct linkages and joints [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 158" title="Kanda T, Hirano T, Eaton D, Ishiguro H. Interactive robots as social partners and peer tutors for children: a field trial. Human–Comput Interact. 2004;19(1–2):61–84." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR158" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2758">158</a>]. Safety difficulties are also generated by differences in elastic modulus across biological cell and robotic components. The need for safe and obedient robots led to the development of soft-bodied robots (Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig9">9</a>). Soft-bodied robots possess a remarkable level of flexibility thanks to their adaptable structures, allowing them to approach tasks differently from traditional robots. Unlike their rigid counterparts, soft robots can handle irregular tasks with simplicity rather than complexity. Their ability to continuously alter their shape grants them a unique advantage in navigating unpredictable environments and completing tasks with ease [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 159" title="da Veiga T, Chandler JH, Lloyd P, Pittiglio G, Wilkinson NJ, Hoshiar AK, Harris RA, Valdastri P. Challenges of continuum robots in clinical context: a review. Progr Biomed Eng. 2020;2(3): 032003." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR159" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2764">159</a>].</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-9" data-title="Fig. 9"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig9" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 9</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig9_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-9-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig9_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 9" loading="lazy" width="685" height="330"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/9" data-track-dest="link:Figure9 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 9" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-9-desc"><p>Schematic presentation of the use of hydrogels in soft robotics</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Moreover, hydrogels consist of flexible substances with a similar elasticity to the soft tissues found in living organisms. This quality allows them to interact smoothly and without discomfort with people. The significant progress in utilizing suitable materials to fulfill the increasing need for soft robots has been remarkable. Hydrogels, which are three-dimensional elastic solids created by cross-linked polymer chains in a network structure of water and hydrophilic polymer chains, play a vital role in this area [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 160" title="Zou C, Chen L, Liu Q, Lu W, Sun X, Liu J, Lei Y, Zhao W, Liu Y. Flexible aluminum-air battery based on high-performance three-dimensional dual-network PVA/KC/KOH composite gel polymer electrolyte. Langmuir. 2024;40:9999." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR160" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2788">160</a>]. Hydrogels are remarkable materials known for their ability to endure repeated mechanical strain, thanks to the adaptable structure of their polymer network. Their flexibility, with an elastic modulus ranging from 1 to 100 kPa, sets them apart from other materials, mainly because of the high-water content they contain. Achieving biocompatibility involves incorporating non-toxic polymers into the hydrogel's network, which makes them suitable for a wide range of biological applications, particularly in soft robotics. Their transparency, almost 99% even in bulk, results from the polymer network's minimal absorption of visible light, enabling the transmission of optical information. Moreover, their responsiveness to external stimuli, due to interactions between the polymer network and water, enhances the functionality of soft robots.</p><p>3D-printed soft robotics possess remarkable flexibility, enabling them to adapt to complex scenarios for a wide range of advanced actuating functions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 161" title="Khalid MY, Arif ZU, Tariq A, Hossain M, Ahmed Khan K, Umer R. 3D printing of magneto-active smart materials for advanced actuators and soft robotics applications. Eur Polym J. 2024;205: 112718. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.eurpolymj.2023.112718&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR161" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2794">161</a>]. While smart materials can sense and react to typical environmental conditions, they are limited in their ability to improve or optimize their response when sudden changes occur in their surroundings. In contrast, intelligent materials are designed to adjust to such shifts, responding effectively and purposefully to enhance and refine their performance [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 162" title="Arif ZU, Khalid MY, Ahmed W, Arshad H. A review on four-dimensional (4D) bioprinting in pursuit of advanced tissue engineering applications. Bioprinting. 2022;27: e00203. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bprint.2022.e00203&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR162" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2797">162</a>]. Both smart and intelligent materials are continually advancing for use in various artificial actuators. The movements of these actuators often draw inspiration from natural systems, mimicking life-like motions in bioinspired robotics. Additionally, these materials provide capabilities beyond conventional ones, especially for the creation of unique actuators, thanks to their inherent ability to adapt and deform in response to environmental stimuli. Smart materials encompass a range of features, including self-healing, self-transforming properties, auxetic behavior, and responses to compression and tension, such as softening and hardening. They can also exhibit action-at-a-distance phenomena and undergo gradual changes, assembling into new forms through bending, spreading, twisting, shrinking, and folding. These dynamic behaviors, combined with 3D-printed complex geometries, make these materials ideal for applications in soft robotics, advanced actuators, biomimetic devices, and self-deployable structures.</p><p>The presence of mobile ions dissolved in water imparts ionic conductivity to hydrogels, reaching up to ~ 10 S/m. Although hydrogels exhibit higher resistivity compared to other soft electrical materials, the increase in electrical resistance with strain is orders of magnitude lower [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 163" title="Lee JH, Hyun JE, Kim J, Yang J, Zhang H, Ahn H, Lee S, Kim JH, Lim T. A highly conductive, robust, self-healable, and thermally responsive liquid metal-based hydrogel for reversible electrical switches. J Mater Chem B. 2024;12:5238." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR163" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2803">163</a>]. This makes hydrogels suitable for use as electrodes in applications requiring high stretchability, such as in soft robots. Moreover, the ability of hydrogels to accommodate additives larger than the mesh of the polymer network enhances their versatility. This feature allows hydrogels to be equipped with a multitude of functions, making them a promising material for soft robots [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 164" title="Ye Z, Zheng L, Chen W, Wang B, Zhang L. Recent advances in bioinspired soft robots: fabrication, actuation, tracking, and applications. Adv Mater Technol. 2024;9:2301862." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR164" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2806">164</a>]. In this comprehensive review, we investigate soft robots made from hydrogels, examining five key elements: actuators, sensors, communication systems, power supplies, and computational circuits. Furthermore, we explore alternative soft robotic components using organ gels and ion gels, which substitute water with organic solvents and ionic liquids, respectively [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 165" title="Sheikh K, Hossain KR, Hossain MA, Sagar MSI, Raju MRH, Haque F. 3D printed ionic liquids based hydrogels and applications. J Ionic Liquids. 2024;2024: 100093." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR165" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2809">165</a>]. We offer a detailed examination of how each component functions, highlighting the crucial contributions of hydrogels.</p><h3 class="c-article__sub-heading" id="Sec100"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5 </span>Stimuli Responsive Hydrogels</h3><h4 class="c-article__sub-heading c-article__sub-heading--small" id="Sec17"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5.1 </span>Glucose-responsive hydrogel</h4><p>Hyperglycemia stands as a significant challenge in the treatment of diabetic wounds [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 166" title="Burgess JL, Wyant WA, Abdo Abujamra B, Kirsner RS, Jozic I. Diabetic wound-healing science. Medicina. 2021;57(10):1072." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR166" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2824">166</a>]. Researchers have responded by developing a range of glucose-responsive hydrogel wound dressings [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 167" title="Zhao L, Niu L, Liang H, Tan H, Liu C, Zhu F. pH and glucose dual-responsive injectable hydrogels with insulin and fibroblasts as bioactive dressings for diabetic wound healing. ACS Appl Mater Interfaces. 2017;9(43):37563–74." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR167" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2827">167</a>]. These dressings offer a unique ability to adapt their structure in direct response to changes in glucose levels, thereby enabling controlled release of drugs. The hydrogels fall into three main categories: those incorporating glucose oxidase (GOX), concanavalin A (Con A), and phenylboronic acid (PBA) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 168" title="Wu Q, Wang L, Yu H, Wang J, Chen Z. Organization of glucose-responsive systems and their properties. Chem Rev. 2011;111(12):7855–75." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR168" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2830">168</a>]. While GOX and Con A are natural proteins prized for their glucose specificity, PBA is a synthetic receptor capable of binding to glucose molecules.</p><p>These innovative hydrogels represent a promising avenue for delivering therapeutic agents like insulin in a glucose-dependent manner, potentially offering enhanced wound healing for diabetic patients [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 168" title="Wu Q, Wang L, Yu H, Wang J, Chen Z. Organization of glucose-responsive systems and their properties. Chem Rev. 2011;111(12):7855–75." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR168" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2836">168</a>]. For instance, a hydrogel dressing infused with PBA demonstrated remarkable glucose-responsive insulin release, leading to reduced inflammation and improved wound healing in diabetic mice [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 169" title="Tong M-Q, Luo L-Z, Xue P-P, Han Y-H, Wang L-F, Zhuge D-L, Yao Q, Chen B, Zhao Y-Z, Xu H-L. Glucose-responsive hydrogel enhances the preventive effect of insulin and liraglutide on diabetic nephropathy of rats. Acta Biomater. 2021;122:111–32." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR169" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2839">169</a>]. However, it's important to note that while PBA-based hydrogels boast stability, they may exhibit less selectivity towards glucose compared to their natural protein counterparts [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 168" title="Wu Q, Wang L, Yu H, Wang J, Chen Z. Organization of glucose-responsive systems and their properties. Chem Rev. 2011;111(12):7855–75." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR168" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2842">168</a>]. Furthermore, GOX-based hydrogels not only have the ability to lower pH levels but also demonstrate antibacterial properties, which could be advantageous in the context of wound healing [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 170" title="He S, Lin M, Zheng Q, Liang B, He X, Zhang Y, Xu Q, Deng H, Fan K, Chen W. Glucose oxidase energized osmium with dual-active centers and triple enzyme activities for infected diabetic wound management. Adv Healthc Mater. 2024;13:2303548." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR170" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2845">170</a>]. Yet, the use of GOX-based dressings may necessitate careful monitoring of wound pH levels due to potential alterations caused by glucose consumption. On the other hand, Con A-based hydrogels have faced challenges regarding stability and biocompatibility [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 171" title="Wu H, Wang J, Fan W, Zhong Q, Xue R, Li S, Song Z, Tao Y. Eye of the future: unlocking the potential utilization of hydrogels in intraocular lenses. Bioeng Transl Med. 2024;9: e10664." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR171" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2848">171</a>]. Despite these hurdles, glucose-responsive hydrogel dressings hold tremendous promise for improving the treatment of diabetic wounds. However, continued research efforts are essential to refine their performance and address existing limitations.</p><h4 class="c-article__sub-heading c-article__sub-heading--small" id="Sec18"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5.2 </span>Temperature-responsive hydrogel</h4><p>Wound healing is intricately linked to temperature due to the temperature-dependency of many enzyme response rates [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 172" title="Hajfathalian M, Mossburg KJ, Radaic A, Woo KE, Jonnalagadda P, Kapila Y, Bollyky PL, Cormode DP. A review of recent advances in the use of complex metal nanostructures for biomedical applications from diagnosis to treatment. Wiley Interdiscip Rev Nanomed Nanobiotechnol. 2024;16(3): e1959." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR172" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2859">172</a>]. Additionally, temperature serves as a key indicator in evaluating chronic wounds and may also influence the effectiveness of responsive wound dressings. A recent study by Lin et al. explored the correlation between wound temperature and healing, revealing that higher peri wound temperatures can expedite the healing process, as observed in patients with pressure ulcers [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 173" title="Lin Y-H, Chen Y-C, Cheng K-S, Yu P-J, Wang J-L, Ko N-Y. Higher periwound temperature associated with wound healing of pressure ulcers detected by infrared thermography. J Clin Med. 2021;10(13):2883." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR173" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2862">173</a>]. Similarly, Fierheller et al. observed temperature changes around wounds, particularly noting a significant increase in temperature during infection in patients with chronic leg ulcers [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 174" title="Fierheller M, Sibbald RG. A clinical investigation into the relationship between increased periwound skin temperature and local wound infection in patients with chronic leg ulcers. Adv Skin Wound Care. 2010;23(8):369–79." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR174" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2865">174</a>]. Innovations such as temperature-responsive hydrogels offer promising solutions, adapting to temperature variations to optimize wound coverage and drug release. These hydrogels can transition between solution and gel phases, with pharmaceuticals being released as the hydrogel shrinks or expands in response to temperature changes. Zhang et al. developed GelMA-PDA-ASP, a temperature-responsive hydrogel dressing that demonstrated superior wound healing efficacy compared to traditional dressings in murine models [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 175" title="Zhang K, Lv H, Zheng Y, Yao Y, Li X, Yu J, Ding B. Nanofibrous hydrogels embedded with phase-change materials: temperature-responsive dressings for accelerating skin wound healing. Compos Commun. 2021;25: 100752. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.coco.2021.100752&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR175" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2868">175</a>]. Heilmann et al. have explored using hydrogel dressings as carriers for medications like morphine, ensuring sustained drug release for prolonged pain relief [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 176" title="Heilmann S, Küchler S, Wischke C, Lendlein A, Stein C, Schäfer-Korting M. A thermosensitive morphine-containing hydrogel for the treatment of large-scale skin wounds. Int J Pharm. 2013;444(1):96–102. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijpharm.2013.01.027&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR176" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2871">176</a>]. Wu et al., developed a 3D-printed self-healing hydrogel based on PU/gelatin [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 177" title="Wu S-D, Hsu S-H. 4D bioprintable self-healing hydrogel with shape memory and cryopreserving properties. Biofabrication. 2021;13(4): 045029. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1088/1758-5090/ac2789&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR177" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2875">177</a>]. This innovative material exhibited remarkable photo- and thermo-responsive properties, achieving shape stability (~ 95%) and excellent shape recovery (~ 98%) during the water lattice formation and collapse processes. Additionally, these 4D bioprinted hydrogels retained their functionality after being cryopreserved at either − 20 °C or − 80 °C and subsequently restored to their original shape at 37 °C, indicating significant potential for use in customized biofabrication for a variety of biomedical applications [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 178" title="Arif ZU, Khalid MY, Tariq A, Hossain M, Umer R. 3D printing of stimuli-responsive hydrogel materials: literature review and emerging applications. Giant. 2024;17: 100209. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.giant.2023.100209&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR178" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2878">178</a>]. In a separate study, Huang et al., explored nanocomposite hydrogels incorporating PAM/PAA with lignin sulfonate nanorods in a water/glycerol solvent mixture [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 179" title="Huang J, Wan Y, Wang M, Yang J, Sun F, Abdulkhani A, Liu X, Nawaz H, Xu F, Zhang X. Lignin nanorods reinforced nanocomposite hydrogels with UV-shielding, anti-freezing and anti-drying applications. Ind Crops Prod. 2022;187: 115324. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.indcrop.2022.115324&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR179" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2881">179</a>]. These hydrogels demonstrate effective UV-blocking capabilities and enhanced mechanical properties. Moreover, these nanocomposite hydrogels, when combined with glycerol, exhibited outstanding stability at extremely low temperatures (− 60 °C and − 20 °C) for up to a week without freezing. Gao and his team investigated graphene oxide (GO)-modified poly(<i>N</i>-isopropylacrylamide) (PNIPAM) hydrogels, which showed promise for wound dressing applications due to their temperature-responsive properties [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 180" title="Gao D, Li G, Qu X, Li X, Xu X, Li Y, Zhou Z. Thermo-responsive hydrogel with tunable transition temperature for effective drug release. Mater Lett. 2022;321: 132367. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.matlet.2022.132367&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR180" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2887">180</a>]. They also revealed that the compression strength of the hybrid hydrogels was 49 times greater than that of PNIPAM alone, and the transition temperature was highly adjustable, ranging from 32.7 °C to 34.8 °C. Notably, the effectiveness of temperature-responsive hydrogel dressings is contingent upon precise temperature control throughout production, transportation, and storage, considering both environmental and physiological factors [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 177" title="Wu S-D, Hsu S-H. 4D bioprintable self-healing hydrogel with shape memory and cryopreserving properties. Biofabrication. 2021;13(4): 045029. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1088/1758-5090/ac2789&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR177" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2890">177</a>]. Therefore, comprehensive understanding and management of temperature variations are essential for optimizing the therapeutic potential of such dressings across different conditions and settings.</p><h4 class="c-article__sub-heading c-article__sub-heading--small" id="Sec19"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5.3 </span>pH-responsive hydrogel dressing</h4><p>Hydrogel based dressings with pH-responsive properties offer a dynamic solution for controlled drug release, catering to specific therapeutic needs while minimizing adverse effects and optimizing treatment outcomes [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 181" title="Naghib SM, Amiri S, Mozafari MR. Stimuli-responsive chitosan-based nanocarriers for drug delivery in wound dressing applications: a review. Carbohydr Polym Technol Appl. 2024;7: 100497. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.carpta.2024.100497&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR181" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2901">181</a>]. The fluctuating pH levels during different stages of wound healing serve as a natural cue for regulating drug delivery, thereby influencing the healing process itself.</p><p>Among the array of materials used in wound dressings, hyaluronic acid (HA) stands out for its innate ability to facilitate cell migration and associated signaling, promoting wound healing [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 182" title="Astaneh ME, Fereydouni N. A focused review on hyaluronic acid contained nanofiber formulations for diabetic wound healing. Int J Biol Macromol. 2023;253: 127607. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2023.127607&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR182" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2907">182</a>]. Research conducted by Lee et al. demonstrated the efficacy of pure HA dressing (Healoderm) in treating Diabetic Foot Ulcers, highlighting its potential to expedite healing without undue side effects [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 183" title="Lee M, Han SH, Choi WJ, Chung KH, Lee JW. Hyaluronic acid dressing (Healoderm) in the treatment of diabetic foot ulcer: a prospective, randomized, placebo-controlled, single-center study. Wound Repair Regen. 2016;24(3):581–8. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1111/wrr.12428&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR183" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2910">183</a>]. Building upon this foundation, Li et al. innovated a multifunctional hydrogel dressing integrating <i>N</i>-carboxylethyl chitosan (<i>N</i>-chitosan), adipic acid dihydrazide (ADH), and in situ cross-linked HA-aldehyde (HA-ALD), loaded with insulin glargine for sustained release and pH responsiveness. This formulation exhibited accelerated wound healing and mitigated peripheral neuropathy in diabetic rats.</p><p>Polyelectrolyte complex hydrogels, synthesized via ionic cross-linking, involve high molecular weight ionic molecules, particularly polyelectrolytes with a specific molecular weight distribution (Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#Fig10">10</a>) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 184" title="Rumon MMH, Akib AA, Sarkar SD, Khan MAR, Uddin MM, Nasrin D, Roy CK. Polysaccharide-based hydrogels for advanced biomedical engineering applications. ACS Polymers Au. 2024. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acspolymersau.4c00028&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR184" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2925">184</a>]. The main interaction in these complexes is the electrostatic attraction between the cationic groups of one chitosan chain and the anionic groups of another (such as cellulose). This mechanism is closely tied to the volume phase transition, which is triggered by pH shifts and changes in ionic strength. A drop in pH can induce gelation in polysaccharide solutions, used alone or combined with other gelation techniques, to form gel particles from materials such as chitosan, pectin, and alginic acid [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 185" title="Ching SH, Bansal N, Bhandari B. Alginate gel particles—a review of production techniques and physical properties. Crit Rev Food Sci Nutr. 2017;57(6):1133–52. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1080/10408398.2014.965773&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR185" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2928">185</a>]. The gelation process begins at the interface when a polymer solution contacts an acidic or basic environment, and the process continues as ions diffuse through the solution, eventually forming a solid shell. For alginic acid, gelation occurs when the pH falls below the polymer’s dissociation constant [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 186" title="Chan AW, Whitney RA, Neufeld RJ. Kinetic controlled synthesis of pH-responsive network alginate. Biomacromol. 2008;9(9):2536–45. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/bm800594f&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR186" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2931">186</a>]. The speed at which the pH changes is crucial: a rapid decrease leads to precipitation, while a gradual decline results in bulk gel formation. In contrast to ionic gels, alginate gels are stabilized by hydrogen bonds between carboxyl groups on different polymer chains, while pectin gelation is driven by hydrophobic interactions [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 187" title="Li K, Liu X, Jiang F, Zhang B, Qiao D, Xie F. In the process of polysaccharide gel formation: a review of the role of competitive relationship between water and alcohol molecules. Int J Biol Macromol. 2024;281: 136398. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2024.136398&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR187" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2934">187</a>]. Chitosan forms gels at higher pH levels, and its gel particles are created by exposing the polymer to an alkaline medium. Similarly, cellulose can be coagulated using strong acids like sulfuric, nitric, or hydrochloric acid, which act as nonsolvent and facilitate gel formation.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-10" data-title="Fig. 10"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig10" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 10</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig10_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-10-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs43939-025-00178-x/MediaObjects/43939_2025_178_Fig10_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 10" loading="lazy" width="685" height="267"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x/figures/10" data-track-dest="link:Figure10 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 10" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-10-desc"><p><b>a</b> Overview of the pH-sensitive structural changes and swelling behavior in polysaccharide-based polyelectrolyte complex hydrogels. <b>b</b> Common response of a pH-responsive polymeric hydrogel in drug delivery systems. Under acidic conditions, the cationic hydrogel expands and contracts in alkaline environments, releasing its payload. On the other hand, anionic hydrogels undergo swelling in basic environments and contract when exposed to acidic conditions. Adopted with permission from ref. [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 184" title="Rumon MMH, Akib AA, Sarkar SD, Khan MAR, Uddin MM, Nasrin D, Roy CK. Polysaccharide-based hydrogels for advanced biomedical engineering applications. ACS Polymers Au. 2024. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acspolymersau.4c00028&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR184" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2953">184</a>] Copyright 2024, American Chemical Society</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Addressing the prevalent issue of diabetic wound infections, silver nanoparticles (AgNPs) find application in antibacterial hydrogel dressings alongside antibiotics [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 188" title="Khan MAR, Habib MA, Naime J, Hasan Rumon MM, Shamim Al Mamun M, NazmulIslam ABM, Mahiuddin M, Rezaul Karim KM, Hosna Ara M. A review on synthesis, characterizations, and applications of Schiff base functionalized nanoparticles. Results Chem. 2023;6: 101160. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rechem.2023.101160&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR188" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2967">188</a>]. For instance, the Aquacel Ag dressing combines silver with hydrofiber, ensuring a prolonged release for enhanced bactericidal effect. However, limitations arise from the inability to adjust drug release based on varying wound conditions. On the other hand, Hu et al. devised a double-cross-linked pH-responsive hydrogel encapsulating AgNPs and the angiogenic drug DFO (hydrogel@AgNPs&amp;DFO) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 189" title="Sonamuthu J, Cai Y, Liu H, Kasim MSM, Vasanthakumar VR, Pandi B, Wang H, Yao J. MMP-9 responsive dipeptide-tempted natural protein hydrogel-based wound dressings for accelerated healing action of infected diabetic wound. Int J Biol Macromol. 2020;153:1058–69. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2019.10.236&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR189" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2970">189</a>]. This formulation displayed dual properties of antibacterial action and angiogenesis promotion, offering tailored drug release rates based on pH variations. In diabetic rats with bacterial infections, this hydrogel effectively accelerated wound healing, underscoring its clinical relevance.</p><p>In the field of multifunctional wound dressings, the dynamics of drug release significantly influence treatment efficacy [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 190" title="Yang S, Li X, Liu P, Zhang M, Wang C, Zhang B. Multifunctional chitosan/polycaprolactone nanofiber scaffolds with varied dual-drug release for wound-healing applications. ACS Biomater Sci Eng. 2020;6(8):4666–76. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsbiomaterials.0c00674&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR190" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2977">190</a>]. Leveraging pH responsiveness in wound environments enables precise drug delivery, circumventing the need for frequent administration and minimizing the risk of drug resistance [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 191" title="Abdella S, Abid F, Youssef SH, Kim S, Afinjuomo F, Malinga C, Song Y, Garg S. pH and its applications in targeted drug delivery. Drug Discov Today. 2023;28(1): 103414. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.drudis.2022.103414&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR191" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2980">191</a>]. However, this approach introduces challenges in dressing production, necessitating a delicate balance between the dressing's pH compatibility and its responsiveness to the wound site's pH fluctuations, ensuring both therapeutic efficacy and patient comfort [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 192" title="Saghazadeh S, Rinoldi C, Schot M, Kashaf SS, Sharifi F, Jalilian E, Nuutila K, Giatsidis G, Mostafalu P, Derakhshandeh H, et al. Drug delivery systems and materials for wound healing applications. Adv Drug Deliv Rev. 2018;127:138–66. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.addr.2018.04.008&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR192" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2983">192</a>].</p><h4 class="c-article__sub-heading c-article__sub-heading--small" id="Sec20"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5.4 </span>ROS-responsive hydrogel</h4><p>High levels of reactive oxygen species (ROS) pose a significant challenge to the healing process of diabetic wounds, prompting extensive exploration into responsive hydrogels within research circles [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 193" title="Tyagi N, Gambhir K, Kumar S, Gangenahalli G, Verma YK. Interplay of reactive oxygen species (ROS) and tissue engineering: a review on clinical aspects of ROS-responsive biomaterials. J Mater Sci. 2021;56(30):16790–823. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s10853-021-06338-7&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR193" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2994">193</a>]. Zhao et al. introduced a groundbreaking ROS-scavenging hydrogel designed to counteract heightened ROS concentrations in the wound microenvironment [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 194" title="Zhao H, Huang J, Li Y, Lv X, Zhou H, Wang H, Xu Y, Wang C, Wang J, Liu Z. ROS-scavenging hydrogel to promote healing of bacteria infected diabetic wounds. Biomaterials. 2020;258: 120286. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biomaterials.2020.120286&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR194" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e2997">194</a>]. This innovative hydrogel, enriched with antibiotics and granulocyte–macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF), demonstrates remarkable potential in fostering tissue regeneration. By effectively reducing intracellular ROS levels, curtailing pro-inflammatory factor secretion, orchestrating macrophage phenotype alteration, and facilitating the formation of new blood vessels and collagen, this hydrogel markedly enhances wound healing capacity [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 195" title="Xiong Y, Chu X, Yu T, Knoedler S, Schroeter A, Lu L, Zha K, Lin Z, Jiang D, Rinkevich Y, et al. Reactive oxygen species-scavenging nanosystems in the treatment of diabetic wounds. Adv Healthcare Mater. 2023;12(25):2300779. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/adhm.202300779&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR195" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3000">195</a>].</p><p>Another notable advancement in this domain involves the utilization of quaternized chitosan (QCS) and tannin, both revered for their inherent properties beneficial to wound management [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 196" title="Budiarso IJ, Rini NDW, Tsalsabila A, Birowosuto MD, Wibowo A. Chitosan-based smart biomaterials for biomedical applications: progress and perspectives. ACS Biomater Sci Eng. 2023;9(6):3084–115. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsbiomaterials.3c00216&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR196" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3006">196</a>]. Pan et al. engineered an injectable hydrogel (QT) derived from QCS and tannic acid (TA), boasting formidable hemostatic, antibacterial, and ROS-clearance capabilities [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 197" title="Pan W, Qi X, Xiang Y, You S, Cai E, Gao T, Tong X, Hu R, Shen J, Deng H. Facile formation of injectable quaternized chitosan/tannic acid hydrogels with antibacterial and ROS scavenging capabilities for diabetic wound healing. Int J Biol Macromol. 2022;195:190–7. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2021.12.007&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR197" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3009">197</a>]. This hydrogel exhibits exceptional efficacy in minimizing blood loss during surgical procedures and expediting wound closure, as evidenced in diabetic rat skin models. Similarly, Ni et al. capitalized on the antioxidant attributes of TA, synergizing it with phenylboronic acid-modified polyphosphazonitrilene (PPBA) and PVA to develop an ROS-responsive and anti-inflammatory hydrogel (PPBA-TA-PVA) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 142" title="Ni Z, Yu H, Wang L, Huang Y, Lu H, Zhou H, Liu Q. Multistage ROS-responsive and natural polyphenol-driven prodrug hydrogels for diabetic wound healing. ACS Appl Mater Interfaces. 2022;14(47):52643–58. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsami.2c15686&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR142" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3012">142</a>]. Noteworthy is the dynamic phenylborate linkage in PPBA-TA-PVA hydrogels, which imparts injectability and self-healing properties, enabling tailored application to irregular deep wounds. In vivo experiments underscored the superiority of PPBA-TA-PVA hydrogel over conventional Tegaderm films, demonstrating accelerated wound healing and reduced inflammatory duration in diabetic rat wounds.</p><p>The precise modulation of wound microenvironments holds paramount importance in addressing the challenges posed by recalcitrant diabetic wounds, where excessive ROS levels are implicated in delayed healing and infection susceptibility. Responsive hydrogel dressings emerge as a promising avenue, facilitating controlled drug release and ROS reduction at the wound site to foster a conducive healing milieu. Nevertheless, striking a delicate balance in maintaining physiological ROS levels warrants consideration, as optimal ROS concentrations exhibit bactericidal properties and promote wound repair.</p><h4 class="c-article__sub-heading c-article__sub-heading--small" id="Sec21"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5.5 </span>pH/ROS-responsive hydrogel</h4><p>Diabetic wounds often harbor stubborn bacterial infections, leading to a decrease in pH levels and an extended inflammatory phase [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 198" title="Kalan LR, Brennan MB. The role of the microbiome in nonhealing diabetic wounds. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2019;1435(1):79–92. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1111/nyas.13926&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR198" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3027">198</a>]. This exacerbates the concentration of reactive oxygen species (ROS), complicating clinical treatment. However, innovative pH/ROS-responsive hydrogel dressings offer a solution by facilitating sequential drug release [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 199" title="Chen Y, Wang X, Tao S, Wang Q, Ma P-Q, Li Z-B, Wu Y-L, Li D-W. Research advances in smart responsive-hydrogel dressings with potential clinical diabetic wound healing properties. Mil Med Res. 2023;10(1):37. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1186/s40779-023-00473-9&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR199" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3030">199</a>]. Guo et al. developed hydrogels with pH responsiveness through a dynamic Schiff-base mechanism, using gelatin and ODex [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 200" title="Guo C, Wu Y, Li W, Wang Y, Kong Q. Development of a microenvironment-responsive hydrogel promoting chronically infected diabetic wound healing through sequential hemostatic, antibacterial, and angiogenic activities. ACS Appl Mater Interfaces. 2022;14(27):30480–92. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsami.2c02725&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR200" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3033">200</a>]. These gels, infused with antimicrobial zinc oxide nanoparticles and paeoniflorin (Pf)-coated micelles, not only enhance hemostasis but also enable the sequential release of antibacterial and angiogenic medicines. Similarly, Wu et al. utilized dynamic covalent bonds in their gels, incorporating phenylboronic acid-grafted oxyglucan and caffeic acid-grafted ε-polylysine (CE) [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 201" title="Wu Y, Wang Y, Long L, Hu C, Kong Q, Wang Y. A spatiotemporal release platform based on pH/ROS stimuli-responsive hydrogel in wound repairing. J Control Release. 2022;341:147–65. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jconrel.2021.11.027&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR201" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3036">201</a>]. These gels were loaded with diclofenac sodium (DS) and pH-sensitive micelles containing mangiferin (MF), which enabled rapid release of DS and CE in the acidic, ROS-rich environment of diabetic wounds, promoting anti-bacterial conditions and limiting inflammation. Meanwhile, MF was released slowly to promote angiogenesis, facilitating wound healing in diabetic rats. This controlled release of medicines tailored to the wound environment shows promise for clinical applications, despite the rigorous preparation and evaluation required for such dual-responsive dressings.</p><h4 class="c-article__sub-heading c-article__sub-heading--small" id="Sec22"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5.6 </span>pH/temperature-responsive hydrogel</h4><p>Hydrogel dressings with pH/temperature sensitivity offer notable advantages for treating diabetic wounds [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 202" title="Dong R, Guo B. Smart wound dressings for wound healing. Nano Today. 2021;41: 101290. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.nantod.2021.101290&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR202" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3047">202</a>]. They swiftly transform into a gel at the wound site, enhancing drug adhesion and concentration locally. This gel is then broken down as pH levels change, aiding in the elimination of the dressing.</p><p>PNIPAM, with a critical temperature of 32.0 °C, undergoes a shift from being soluble to insoluble spontaneously. This transition can be manipulated by altering hydrophilic monomers. Haidari et al. devised a hydrogel combining N-PNIPAM and PAA, loaded with ultrafine AgNP, for responsive wound treatment [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 203" title="Haidari H, Vasilev K, Cowin AJ, Kopecki Z. Bacteria-activated dual pH- and temperature-responsive hydrogel for targeted elimination of infection and improved wound healing. ACS Appl Mater Interfaces. 2022;14(46):51744–62. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1021/acsami.2c15659&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR203" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3053">203</a>]. The N-PNIPAM's critical temperature increased to 36.5 °C after co-polymerization with PAA, forming a hydrogel close to body temperature. The PAA affected the gel swelling behavior with pH increase, progressively releasing AgNPs. In vivo trials showcased the hydrogel's ability to release Ag ions as needed, effectively combating bacterial infections in rat wounds, hinting at potential clinical applications.</p><p>Pluronic F127, characterized by a PEG-PPG-PEG structure, exhibits reverse thermal gelation, transitioning from liquid to gel as temperature rises. Despite these benefits, external factors can affect skin temperature, impacting the efficacy of temperature-responsive dressings. Stricter conditions for storage and application may limit their widespread use in clinical settings.</p><h4 class="c-article__sub-heading c-article__sub-heading--small" id="Sec23"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7.5.7 </span>Photo/magnetic-responsive hydrogel</h4><p>Apart from the inherent stimulation happening at the injury location, external influences such as light, magnetic fields, and electric fields have the potential to trigger smart drug delivery mechanisms. Magnetic fields and near infrared light are particularly advantageous in addressing deep wounds because they can penetrate tissues effectively. Yang et al [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 109" title="Liu L, Xu M, Ye Y, Zhang B. On the degradation of (micro)plastics: degradation methods, influencing factors, environmental impacts. Sci Total Environ. 2022;806: 151312. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2021.151312&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR109" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3067">109</a>]. devised a method using MXene-based hydrogel combined with Fe<sub>3</sub>O<sub>4</sub>@SiO<sub>2</sub> magnetic nanoparticles (MNPs@MXene) for this purpose. This hydrogel, which is part of a PNIPAM-alginate dual network hydrogel (NIPAM-Alg), has shown great promise in various applications. The addition of AgNPs boosts its antibacterial capabilities significantly. When subjected to either NIR light or an external alternating magnetic field, the MNPs generate heat, causing the hydrogel to contract, resulting in rapid medication release. Studies have demonstrated that applying external stimuli to MXene-based hydrogels enables precise and controlled drug release, particularly effective in treating deeply infected wounds. However, the intricate nature of wound environments demands dressings capable of sensitively adapting to changes. While externally regulating drug release can be advantageous, it necessitates accurate and timely monitoring of the wound-healing process. Therefore, it's recommended that such systems be administered under professional healthcare supervision rather than being integrated into a patient's daily routine.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Conclusion and future aspect"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec24-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec24"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">8 </span>Conclusion and future aspect</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec24-content"><p>In summary, the development of mechanically robust hydrogels represents a significant advancement in biomaterials for medical purposes, overcoming the limitations of conventional hydrogels [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 9" title="Fuchs S, Shariati K, Ma M. Specialty tough hydrogels and their biomedical applications. Adv Healthcare Mater. 2020;9(2):1901396." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3086">9</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 204" title="Foyt DA, Norman MDA, Yu TTL, Gentleman E. Exploiting advanced hydrogel technologies to address key challenges in regenerative medicine. Adv Healthc Mater. 2018;7(8):1700939. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/adhm.201700939&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR204" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3089">204</a>]. These resilient hydrogels owe their strength to various design strategies such as uniform network structures, mechanisms for dissipating energy, and versatile crosslinkers [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 205" title="Li X, Gong JP. Design principles for strong and tough hydrogels. Nat Rev Mater. 2024. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1038/s41578-024-00672-3&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR205" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3092">205</a>]. Despite progress, the path toward clinically viable materials is early, with challenges like instability in tissue culture medium, prolonged failure in vivo, and compromised stability in aqueous environments persisting. To surmount these obstacles, hydrogels with adjustable degradation rates, non-toxic byproducts, and enhanced resistance to fabrication conditions must be created [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 206" title="Radulescu D-M, Neacsu IA, Grumezescu A-M, Andronescu E. New insights of scaffolds based on hydrogels in tissue engineering. Polymers. 2022;14:799." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR206" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3095">206</a>]. However, crafting robust hydrogels with durable mechanical properties and suitable cellular functions for clinical use remains a significant challenge despite these advancements [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 207" title="Cai R, Shan Y, Du F, Miao Z, Zhu L, Hang L, Xiao L, Wang Z. Injectable hydrogels as promising in situ therapeutic platform for cartilage tissue engineering. Int J Biol Macromol. 2024;261: 129537. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2024.129537&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR207" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3098">207</a>].</p><p>Looking ahead, a promising avenue for advancing hydrogels in biomedical applications involves integrating self-healing capabilities [<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 95" title="Talebian S, Mehrali M, Taebnia N, Pennisi CP, Kadumudi FB, Foroughi J, Hasany M, Nikkhah M, Akbari M, Orive G, et al. Self-healing hydrogels: the next paradigm shift in tissue engineering? Advanced Science. 2019;6(16):1801664. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/advs.201801664&#xA;                  &#xA;                ." href="/article/10.1007/s43939-025-00178-x#ref-CR95" id="ref-link-section-d337571395e3104">95</a>]. Particularly beneficial for enduring load-bearing scenarios, self-repairing materials align well with the regenerative properties of living tissues. However, practical implementation encounters obstacles such as poor mechanical strength, cytotoxic chemistries, prolonged healing times, and compatibility issues. Recent endeavors to enhance the fatigue resistance of hydrogels through the introduction of crystalline domains hold potential, while exploration of catechol-based hydrogels and dipole–dipole/hydrogen bond-reinforced hydrogels for rapid self-healing offers new prospects.</p><p>Future research efforts should aim to systematically explore and optimize the trade-off between the mechanical toughness and biodegradability of polymeric hydrogels. Achieving an ideal balance between these properties is crucial for enhancing the performance and sustainability of hydrogels in diverse biomedical and environmental applications. Understanding the underlying mechanisms that govern this balance, including the role of crosslinking density, polymer architecture, and degradation kinetics, will be essential for designing hydrogels that can meet the specific demands of each application, such as controlled drug delivery, wound healing, or tissue engineering.</p><p>Moving forward, addressing challenges related to biocompatibility and functionalization is crucial. Future research should prioritize enhancing hydrogels with cell-binding motifs, growth factors, and immunomodulatory agents to create artificial matrices that mimic natural microenvironments. This interdisciplinary approach is paramount for developing specialized hydrogels with superior mechanical properties, enhanced bioactivity, and precise micro/nanoarchitecture, ensuring their robust utilization across various biomedical applications. Continued exploration of these avenues promises to propel the field towards more advanced and clinically applicable solutions.</p></div></div></section>
